# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: desktop-computer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A **19-inch rack** is a standardized frame or enclosure for mounting multiple electronic equipment modules.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Each module has a front panel that is 19 inches (482.6 mm) wide.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The 19 inch dimension includes the edges or *ears* that protrude from each side of the equipment, allowing the module to be fastened to the rack frame with screws or bolts.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Common uses include computer servers, telecommunications equipment and networking hardware, audiovisual production gear, professional audio equipment, and scientific equipment.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Equipment designed to be placed in a rack is typically described as **rack-mount**/**rack-mountable**, a **rack-mount instrument**, **rack-mounted system**, or **rack-mount chassis**.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The rack may include subracks or shelves.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The height of the mountable equipment is standardized as multiples of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) or one *rack unit* or *U* (less commonly *RU*).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The industry-standard rack cabinet is 42U tall; however, many data centers have racks taller than this.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The term **relay rack** appeared first in the late 19th century, in the world of telephony.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] By 1911, the term was also being used in railroad signaling.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] There is little evidence that the dimensions of these early racks were standardized.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format with rack units of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) was established as a standard by AT&T around 1922 in order to reduce the space required for repeater and termination equipment in a telephone company central office.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The earliest repeaters from 1914 were installed in ad hoc fashion on shelves, in wooden boxes and cabinets.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Once serial production started, they were built into custom-made racks, one per repeater.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] But in light of the rapid growth of the toll network, the engineering department of AT&T undertook a systematic redesign, resulting in a family of modular factory-assembled panels all "designed to mount on vertical supports spaced 191⁄2 inches between centers.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] By 1934, it was an established standard with holes tapped for 12-24 screws with alternating spacings of 1.25 inches (31.75 mm) and 0.5 inches (12.70 mm).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format has remained constant while the technology that is mounted within it has changed considerably and the set of fields to which racks are applied has greatly expanded.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch (482.6 mm) standard rack arrangement is widely used throughout the telecommunications, computing, audio, video, entertainment and other industries, though the Western Electric 23-inch standard, with holes on 1-inch (25.4 mm) centers, is still used in legacy ILEC/CLEC facilities.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks in two-post or four-post form hold most equipment in enterprise data centers, Internet service provider facilities, and professionally designed corporate server rooms, although hyperscale computing typically use wider racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] They allow for dense hardware configurations without occupying excessive floor space or requiring shelving.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks are also often used to house professional audio and video equipment, including amplifiers, effects units, interfaces, headphone amplifiers, and even small-scale audio mixers.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A third common use for rack-mounted equipment is industrial power, control, and automation hardware.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Typically, a piece of equipment being installed has a front panel height 1⁄32 inch (0.031 in; 0.79 mm) less than the allotted number of Us.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Thus, a 1U rackmount computer is not 1.750 inches (44.5 mm) tall but is 1.719 inches (43.7 mm) tall.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] If *n* is the number of rack units, the ideal formula for panel height is *h* = 1.75*n* − 0.031 for calculating in inches, and *h* = 44.45*n* − 0.794 for calculating in millimeters.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] This gap allows a bit of room above and below an installed piece of equipment so it may be removed without binding on the adjacent equipment.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Originally, the mounting holes were tapped with a particular screw thread.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] When rack rails are too thin to tap, rivet nuts or other threaded inserts can be used, and when the particular class of equipment to be mounted is known in advance, some of the holes can be omitted from the mounting rails.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Threaded mounting holes in racks where the equipment is frequently changed are problematic because the threads can be damaged or the mounting screws can break off; both problems render the mounting hole unusable.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Tapping large numbers of holes that may never be used is expensive; nonetheless, tapped-hole racks are still in use, generally for hardware that rarely changes.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Examples include telephone exchanges, network cabling panels, broadcast studios and some government and military applications.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The tapped-hole rack was first replaced by clearance-hole (Round Hole, Round Unthreaded Holes, and Versa Rail) racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The holes are large enough to permit a bolt to be freely inserted through without binding, and bolts are fastened in place using cage nuts.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] In the event of a nut being stripped out or a bolt breaking, the nut can be easily removed and replaced with a new one.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Production of clearance-hole racks is less expensive.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The next innovation in rack design has been the square-hole rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Square-hole racks allow boltless mounting, such that the rack-mount equipment only needs to insert through and hook down into the lip of the square hole.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Installation and removal of hardware in a square-hole rack is very easy and boltless, where the weight of the equipment and small retention clips are all that is necessary to hold the equipment in place.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Older equipment meant for round-hole or tapped-hole racks can still be used, with the use of cage nuts made for square-hole racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is traditionally mounted by bolting or clipping its front panel to the rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Within the IT industry, it is common for network/communications equipment to have multiple mounting positions, including tabletop and wall mounting, so rack-mountable equipment will often feature L-brackets that must be screwed or bolted to the equipment prior to mounting in a 19-inch rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] With the prevalence of 23-inch racks in the Telecoms industry, the same practice is also common, but with equipment having 19-inch and 23-inch brackets available, enabling them to be mounted in existing racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A key structural weakness of front-mounted support is the bending stress placed on the mounting brackets of the equipment and the rack itself.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] As a result, 4-post racks have become common, featuring a mirrored pair of rear mounting posts.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Servers and deep pieces of equipment are often mounted using rails that are bolted to the front and rear posts (as above, it is common for such rails to have an adjustable depth), allowing the equipment to be supported by four posts, while also enabling it to be easily installed and removed.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] This, of course, varies by manufacturer, the design of the rack and its purpose, but through common constraining factors (such as raised-floor tile dimensions), these dimensions have become quite common.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The extra width and depth enable cabling to be routed with ease (also helping to maintain the minimum bend radius for fiber and copper cables) and deeper equipment to be utilized.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A common feature in IT racks is mounting positions for *zero-U* accessories, such as power distribution units (PDUs) and vertical cable managers and ducts, that utilize the space between the rear rails and the side of the rack enclosure.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The strength required of the mounting posts means they are invariably not merely flat strips but actually a wider folded strip arranged around the corner of the rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The posts are usually made of steel of around 2 mm thickness (the official standard recommends a minimum of 1.9 mm), or of slightly thicker aluminum.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Racks, especially two-post racks, are often secured to the floor or adjacent building structure so as not to fall over.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] This is usually required by local building codes in seismic zones.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] According to Telcordia Technologies Generic Requirements document GR-63-CORE, during an earthquake, telecommunications equipment is subjected to motions that can over-stress the equipment framework, circuit boards, and connectors.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The amount of motion and resulting stress depends on the structural characteristics of the building and framework in which the equipment is contained and the severity of the earthquake.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Seismic racks rated according to GR-63, *NEBS Requirements: Physical Protection,* are available, with Zone 4 representing the most demanding environment.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] GR-3108, *Generic Requirements for Network Equipment in the Outside Plant (OSP),* specifies the usable opening of seismic-compliant 19-inch racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Heavy equipment or equipment that is commonly accessed for servicing, for which attaching or detaching at all four corners simultaneously would pose a problem, is often not mounted directly onto the rack but instead is mounted via rails (or slides).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A pair of rails is mounted directly onto the rack, and the equipment then slides into the rack along the rails, which support it.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] When in place, the equipment may also then be bolted to the rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The rails may also be able to fully support the equipment in a position where it has been slid clear of the rack; this is useful for inspection or maintenance of equipment, which will then be slid back into the rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Some rack slides even include a tilt mechanism allowing easy access to the top or bottom of rack-mounted equipment when it is fully extended from the rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A rails kit may include a cable management arm (CMA), which folds the cables attached to the server and allows them to expand neatly when the server is slid out, without being disconnected.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] When there is a large number of computers in a single rack, it is impractical for each one to have its own separate keyboard, mouse, and monitor.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Instead, a KVM switch or LOM software is used to share a single keyboard/video/mouse set amongst many different computers.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Since the mounting hole arrangement is vertically symmetric, it is possible to mount rack-mountable equipment upside-down.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] However, not all equipment is suitable for this type of mounting.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] For instance, most optical disc players will not work upside-down because the driving motor mechanism does not grip the disc.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A standard 19-inch server rack cabinet is typically 42u in height, 600 millimetres (24 in) wide, and 36 inches (914.40 mm) deep.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] This comprises a volume of 974 L, or just under a cubic meter.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Newer server rack cabinets come with adjustable mounting rails, allowing the user to place the rails at a shorter depth if needed.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] There are a multitude of specialty server racks, including soundproof server racks, air-conditioned server racks, NEMA-rated, seismic-rated, open frame, narrow, and even miniature 19-inch racks for smaller applications.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Cabinets are generally sized to be no wider than the standard 24-inch-wide (610 mm) floor tiles used in most data centers.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Racks carrying telecom equipment like routers and switches often have extra width to accommodate the many cables on the sides.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] 19-inch equipment that needs to be moved often or protected from harsh treatment can be housed in a *road case* approved by the Air Transport Association of America (ATA), sometimes also referred to as a *flight case*.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Road cases typically have plywood sides laminated with polyvinyl chloride (PVC), extruded aluminum edges, steel corners, handles, and latches.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Larger cases typically have wheels for easy transport.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Road case racks come in different heights based on the 1U standard and different depths.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Non-isolated cases simply mount 19-inch mounting posts inside the case.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] To protect equipment from shock and vibration, road rack cases use an inner and outer case.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] These cases can be isolated by thick layers of foam or may use spring-loaded shock mounting.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Touring musicians, theatrical productions and sound and light companies use road case racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Rack strips used for road cases come in 2 types: single angle and double angle.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Double-angle rack strips offer better structural strength and an additional mounting face for cable management or additional support for heavy equipment.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] In 1965, a durable fiber-reinforced plastic 19-inch rackmount case was patented by ECS Composites and became widely used in military and commercial applications for electronic deployment and operation.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Rackmount cases are also constructed of thermo-stamped composite, carbon fiber, and DuPont's Kevlar for military and commercial uses.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Portable rack cases using a rotary-molded polyethylene outer shell are a lower-cost alternative to the more durable ATA-approved case.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] These cases are marketed to musicians and entertainers for equipment not subject to frequent transportation and rough handling.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The polyethylene shell is not fiberglass reinforced and is not rigid.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The shape of small cases is maintained by the rack rails and the cover seal extrusions alone.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Larger cases are further reinforced with additional plywood or sheet metal.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The outer shell is frequently embossed in a self-mating pattern to combat the tendency for stacked cases to deform slightly, creating a slope that encourages the upper case to slide off.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The cases typically use extruded aluminum bands at the ends of the body with tongue-and-groove mating to like bands for the covers.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] End covers are typically secured with either a simple draw latch or a rotary cam *butterfly* latch, named for the shape of the twist handle.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] There is no standard for airflow and cooling of rack-mounted equipment.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A variety of airflow patterns can be found, including front intakes and rear exhausts, as well as side intakes and exhausts.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Low-wattage devices may not employ active cooling, but use only passive thermal radiation and convection to dissipate heat.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] For rack-mounted computer servers, devices generally intake air on the front and exhaust on the rear.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] This prevents circular airflows where hot exhaust air is recirculated through an adjacent device and causes overheating.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Although open-frame racks are the least expensive, they also expose air-cooled equipment to dust, lint, and other environmental contamination.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] An enclosed sealed cabinet with forced air fans permits air filtration to protect equipment from dust.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Large server rooms will often group rack cabinets together so that racks on both sides of an aisle are either front-facing or rear-facing, which simplifies cooling by supplying cool air to the front of the racks and collecting hot air from the rear of the racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] These aisles may themselves be enclosed in a cold air containment tunnel so that cooling air does not travel to other parts of the building where it is not needed or mixes with hot air, making it less efficient.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Raised or false floor cooling in server rooms can serve a similar purpose; they permit cooling airflow to equipment through the underfloor space to the underside of enclosed rack cabinets.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A difficulty with forced air fan cooling in rack equipment is that fans can fail due to age or dust.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The fans themselves can be difficult to replace.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] In the case of network equipment, it may be necessary to unplug 50 or more cables from the device, remove the device from the rack, and then disassemble the device chassis to replace the fans.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] However, some rack equipment has been designed to make fan replacement easy, using quick-change fan trays that can be accessed without removing the cabling or the device from the rack, and in some cases without turning off the device so that operation is uninterrupted during replacement.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A rack's mounting fixture consists of two parallel metal strips (also referred to as *posts* or *panel mounts*) standing vertically.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The posts are each 0.625 inches (15.88 mm) wide, and are separated by a gap of 17.75 inches (450.85 mm), giving an overall rack width of 19 inches (482.60 mm).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The posts have holes in them at regular intervals, with both posts matching, so that each hole is part of a horizontal pair with a center-to-center distance of 18.28–18.34 inches (464.2–465.8 mm).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The holes in the posts are arranged vertically in repeating sets of three, with center-to-center separations of 0.5, 0.625, 0.625 inches (12.70, 15.88, 15.88 mm).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The hole pattern thus repeats every 1.75 inches (44.45 mm).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Holes so arranged can either be tapped (usually 10-32 UNF thread, or, less often, 6mm metric) or have square holes for cage nuts.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Racks are vertically divided into regions, 44.45 millimetres (1.75 in) in height.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Each region has three complete hole pairs on each side.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The holes are centered at 6.35 millimetres (0.25 in), 22.25 millimetres (0.88 in), and 38.1 millimetres (1.50 in) from the top or bottom of the region.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Such a region is commonly known as a **U**, for *unit*, **RU** for *rack unit* or, in German, **HE**, for *Höheneinheit*.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Heights within racks are measured by this unit.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is usually designed to occupy some integer number of U.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] For example, an oscilloscope might be 4U high.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable computers and servers are mostly between 1U and 4U high.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A blade server enclosure might require 10U.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Occasionally, one may see fractional U devices, such as a 1.5U server or devices that are just 22.5 or 15 cm in width, allowing for 2 or 3 such devices to be installed side by side, but these are much less common.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The height of a rack can vary from a few inches, such as in a broadcast console, to a floor-mounted rack whose interior is 45 rack units (200.2 centimetres or 78.82 inches) high.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Many wall-mounted enclosures for industrial equipment use 19-inch racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Some telecommunications and networking equipment is available in a narrower 10-inch format with the same unit height as a standard 19-inch rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] This standard is also gaining in popularity with hobbyists with limited space at their disposal.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Frames for holding rotary-dial telephone equipment, such as step-by-step telephone switches, were generally 11 feet 6 inches (3.51 m) high.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A series of studies led to the adoption of frames 7 feet (2.1 m) high, with modular widths in multiples of 1 foot 1 inch (0.33 m)—most often 2 feet 2 inches (0.66 m) wide.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The **ETSI rack** is defined by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETS 300 119).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The distance of the right edge of the right mounting rail to the left edge of the left mounting rail is 535 millimetres (21.1 in).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] As 535 mm is very close to 21 inches, these racks are sometimes called *21-inch racks*.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The gap between the posts is 500 millimetres (19.69 in).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] As 19-inch equipment has a maximum width of 17+1⁄4 inches (438.15 mm), they can easily be mounted in an ETSI rack by means of an ETSI bracket or adapter plate.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] In contrast to the 19-inch standards, ETSI also defined the size of the rack enclosure: the four allowed widths are 150, 300, 600, 900 millimetres (5.9, 11.8, 23.6, 35.4 in) and two allowed depths are 300 and 600 millimetres (12 and 24 in).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is 25 millimetres (0.98 in).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] A 23-inch (580 mm) rack is used for housing telephone (primarily), computer, audio and other equipment – although it is less common than the 19-inch rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The size denotes the width of the faceplate for the installed equipment.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The rack unit is a measure of vertical spacing and is common to both the 19 and 23-inch racks.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is either on 1-inch (25 mm) centers (Western Electric standard), or the same as for 19-inch (482.6 mm) racks (0.625 in or 15.9 mm spacing).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Open Rack is a mounting system designed by the Open Compute Project that has the same outside dimensions as typical 19-inch racks (e.g., 600 mm width), but internally supports wider equipment modules of 547 millimetres (21.5 in).
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] OpenVPX is an industry standard for modules that can be installed in a chassis in defense applications.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The modules can provide a variety of functions, similar to equipment in a rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Eurorack is a standard generally used in electronic music production to install components of a modular synthesizer, an electronic music instrument.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] This is achieved with a rack mounting system specific to the standard.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Eurocard is an IEEE standard format for printed circuit board (PCB) cards that can be plugged together into a standard chassis, which, in turn, can be mounted in a 19-inch rack.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] The chassis consists of a series of slotted card guides on the top and bottom, into which the cards are slid so they stand on end, like books on a shelf.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] At the spine of each card is one or more connectors which plug into mating connectors on a backplane that closes the rear of the chassis.
[src:desktop-computer/19-inch-rack] Several standards such as VMEbus (Versa Module Eurocard bus), STEbus, PCI eXtensions for Instrumentation, openGear and others were developed, which share goals with Eurocard.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] A **2-in-1 laptop**, also known as a **convertible laptop**, **2-in-1 PC**, **2-in-1 tablet**, **laplet**, **tabtop**, **laptop tablet**, or simply **2-in-1**, is a portable computer that has features of both tablets and laptops.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] 2-in-1 PCs consist of portable computer components within light and thin chassis, and exemplify technological convergence.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] They are convenient for media consumption and non-intensive tasks in tablet mode yet useful for content creation in laptop mode.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Both pre-2-in-1 convertibles and hybrids were crossover devices that combined features of both tablets and laptops.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] The later 2-in-1 PCs comprise a category that is a sibling to both the pre-2-in-1 convertibles and hybrids.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Rotational-convertible format is where in addition to the conventional hinging action, the central single hinge mechanism is also able to rotate about a central axis perpendicular to the keyboard surface, such that the laptop can be turned into a thick tablet.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Most netvertibles have the option to support active (electromagnetic) stylus and/or touchscreen (resistive or capacitive), some being ruggedized such as Panasonic Toughbook CF series.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Other examples include Toshiba Portege M7xx, Fujitsu LifeBook T series and HP EliteBook Revolve series.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] When connected to the keyboard, the display of the detachable can either be free-standing on the hinge or require external support, often in the form of a kickstand.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Novel ways of providing external support include the bending frame and locking mechanism of the HP Spectre x2.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Though the keyboard is usually bundled with the purchase of a 2-in-1 detachable, it is occasionally deemed an optional accessory by manufacturers in order to minimize the starting price of a device.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] In such cases the 2-in-1 detachable is often displayed with its complementary keyboard in advertisements and promotional materials.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] This is true for all devices of the Surface and Surface Pro lines.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Operating systems such as Android even show the mouse cursor when a mouse is connected to a device running it, whereas Ubuntu Touch takes it even further by allowing the user to change the UI to a typical desktop environment which allows for desktop level multitasking, albeit with a smaller display.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] 2-in-1s fall in the category of hybrid or convertible tablets but are distinct in that they run a full-featured desktop operating system and have I/O ports typically found on laptops, such as USB and DisplayPort.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] The most prominent element is the keyboard that allows the 2-in-1 to provide the ergonomic typing experience of a laptop.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] While 2-in-1s fall in a category distinct from laptops, they loosely parallel the traits of the Ultrabook device category, having light and thin chassis, power-efficient CPUs, and long battery lives.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] They are distinguished from traditional Ultrabooks by the inclusion of a touchscreen display and a concealable or detachable keyboard.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] The earliest device that can be considered a 2-in-1 detachable is the Compaq Concerto from 1993.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] It came with Windows 3.1 and Windows for Pen Computing, and had a cabled detachable keyboard, and battery powered stylus.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] In June 1994, IBM introduced the ThinkPad 360P, which features a display that can be rotated backwards and closed down into a pen-operated tablet.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Mainstream attention for 2-in-1 PCs was not achieved until nearly two decades later, when many manufactures showed devices, at that time referred to as "hybrid" devices, at CES 2011.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] While Packard Bell, Acer and HP all had Microsoft Windows based 2-in-1s by 2011, Lenovo released the well reviewed Windows 2-in-1: The X220 Tablet variant of the ThinkPad X220, successor of 2010's ThinkPad X201 Tablet.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] The 12-inch device included a digital stylus housed within the chassis, somewhat ruggedized construction, and a multi-touch screen with a twist and fold hinge.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Microsoft started its own line of 2-in-1s with the introduction of the Surface Pro series, the first of which was released in February 2013.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] It had a 10.6-inch (27 cm) display, Intel Core i5 CPU, and included the Pro Pen stylus and a detachable keyboard that doubled as a protective screen cover.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] In 2015 Microsoft introduced the Surface Book series, which, similar to the Surface Pro series, features a detachable keyboard cover and Surface Pen stylus.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Samsung entered the 2-in-1 PC market with the release of the Windows-based Samsung Galaxy TabPro S, which was released in March 2016.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] It had a 12-inch display, Intel Core m3 CPU, a first-party keyboard attachment, and a TabPro Pen.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Its successor, the Galaxy Book, was released in February 2017.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Coming in a 10.6-inch model and a 12-inch model, the Galaxy Book has an improved detachable keyboard and include an S Pen.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Google entered the 2-in-1 market after it announced the Pixel Slate in October 2018.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] It runs on ChromeOS and features a 12.3-inch display.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] It includes two USB-C ports, but it omits the 3.5mm headphone jack.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] The featured Pixel Keyboard and Pixelbook Pen are sold separately.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Since 2012, a number of other prominent laptop manufacturers, such as Dell, Asus, and Sony have also begun releasing their own 2-in-1s.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] While the iPad Pro has optional Smart Keyboard and Apple Pencil accessories, Apple has yet to release a true 2-in-1 PC in a detachable form-factor and with a similar desktop OS, citing the quote below.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] 2-in-1s are natively supported by the Microsoft Windows, and Google ChromeOS operating systems.
[src:desktop-computer/2-in-1-laptop] Various other Linux distributions also support some touch features of 2-in-1s, though they are generally unsupported by hardware vendors.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The company's original product was the Voodoo Graphics, an add-in card that implemented hardware acceleration of 3D graphics.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The hardware accelerated only 3D rendering, relying on the PC's current video card for 2D support.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Despite this limitation, the Voodoo Graphics product and its follow-up, Voodoo2, were popular.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] It became standard for 3D games to offer support for the company's Glide API.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Renewed interest in 3D gaming led to the success of the company's products and by the second half of the 1990s products combining a 2D output with 3D performance were appearing.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] This was accelerated by the introduction of Microsoft's Direct3D, which provided a single high-performance API that could be implemented on these cards, seriously eroding the value of Glide.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] While 3dfx continued to offer high-performance options, the value proposition was no longer compelling.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] In the late 1990s 3dfx had an infringement lawsuit which combined with lower sales in the latter years led Nvidia to acquire 3dfx for their engineers, which they acquired around one hundred of.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Most of the company's assets were acquired by Nvidia Corporation on December 15, 2000, mostly for intellectual property rights.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The acquisition was accounted for as a purchase by Nvidia and was completed by the first quarter of its fiscal year of 2002.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx ceased supporting its products on February 15, 2001, and filed for bankruptcy on October 15, 2002.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The company was founded on August 24, 1994, as 3D/fx, Inc.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Ross Smith, Gary Tarolli and Scott Sellers, all former employees of Silicon Graphics Inc.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] They were soon joined by Gordie Campbell of TechFarm.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx released its first product, the Voodoo Graphics 3D chip, to manufacturing on November 6, 1995.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The chip is a VGA 3D accelerator that features rendering methods such as point-sampled texture mapping, Z- and double buffering, Gouraud shading, subpixel correction, alpha compositing, and anti-aliasing.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Alongside the chip came 3dfx's Glide API, designed to take full advantage of the Voodoo Graphics' features.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The company stated that Glide's creation was because it found that no existing APIs at the time could fully utilize the chip's capabilities.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] DirectX 3.0 was deemed to be lacking, and OpenGL was regarded as suitable only for CAD/CAM workstations.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The first graphics card to use the chip was Orchid Technology's Righteous 3D, released on October 7, 1996.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The company manufactured only the chips and some reference boards, and initially did not sell any product to consumers; rather, it acted as an OEM supplier for graphics card companies, which designed, manufactured, marketed, and sold their own graphics cards including the Voodoo chipset.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx gained initial fame in the arcade market.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The first arcade machine that 3dfx Voodoo Graphics hardware was used in was a 1996 baseball game featuring a bat controller with motion sensing technology called *ICE Home Run Derby*.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Later that year it was featured in more popular titles, such as Atari's *San Francisco Rush* and *Wayne Gretzky's 3D Hockey*.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx also developed MiniGL after id Software's John Carmack released a 1997 version of *Quake* that used the OpenGL API.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The MiniGL translated OpenGL commands into Glide, and gave 3dfx the advantage as the sole consumer chip company to deliver a functional graphics library driver until 1998.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Towards the end of 1995, the cost of DRAM dropped significantly and 3dfx was able to enter the consumer PC hardware market with aggressive pricing compared to the few previous 3D graphics solutions for computers.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Prior to affordable 3D hardware, games such as *Doom* and *Quake* had compelled video game players to move from their 80386s to 80486s, and then to the Pentium.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] By the end of 1997, the Voodoo Graphics was by far the most widely adopted 3D accelerator among both consumers and software developers.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Voodoo's primary competition was from PowerVR and Rendition.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] PowerVR produced a similar 3D-only add-on card with capable 3D support, although it was not comparable to Voodoo Graphics in either image quality or performance.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx did not see intense competition in the market from cards that offered the combination of 2D and 3D acceleration.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] While these cards, such as the Nvidia NV1, Matrox Mystique, S3 ViRGE, Vérité V1000, and ATI 3D Rage, offered inferior 3D acceleration in terms of image quality, performance, or both, their lower cost and simplicity often appealed to OEM system builders.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] In 1997, 3dfx was working with entertainment company Sega to develop a new video game console hardware platform.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Sega solicited two competing designs: a unit code-named "Katana", developed in Japan using NEC and Imagination Technologies (then VideoLogic) technology, and "Blackbelt", a system designed in the United States using 3dfx technology.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] However, on July 22, 1997, 3dfx announced that Sega was terminating the development contract.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Sega chose to use NEC's PowerVR chipset for its game console, though it still planned to purchase the rights to 3dfx's technology in order to prevent competitors from acquiring it.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx said Sega has still not given a reason as to why it terminated the contract or why it chose NEC's accelerator chipset over 3dfx's.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] "This is a highly competitive market with price wars happening all the time and it would appear that after evaluating a number of choices—and the ramifications each choice brings—Sega went with a decision that it thought was best for the company's longevity," said Mr.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] "Sega has to make a significant move to stay competitive and they need to make it soon.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Sega quickly quashed 3dfx's "Blackbelt" and used the NEC-based "Katana" as the model for the product that would be marketed and sold as the Dreamcast.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx sued Sega for breach of contract, accusing Sega of starting the deal in bad faith in order to take 3dfx technology.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] In early 1998, 3dfx embarked on a new development project.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Rampage development project was new technology for use in a new graphics card that would take approximately two years to develop, and would supposedly be several years ahead of the competition once it debuted.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The company hired hardware and software teams in Austin, Texas, to develop 2D and 3D Windows device drivers for Rampage in the summer of 1998.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The hardware team in Austin initially focused on Rampage, but then worked on transform and lighting (T&L) engines and on MPEG decoder technology.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx announced in January 1999 that its Banshee cards had sold about one million units.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] While Nvidia had yet to launch a product in the add-in board market that sold as well as 3dfx's Voodoo line, the company was gaining steady ground in the OEM market.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Nvidia RIVA TNT was a similar, highly integrated product that had two major advantages in greater 3D speed and 32-bit 3D color support.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx, by contrast, had very limited OEM sales, as the Banshee was adopted only in small numbers by OEMs.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx executed a major strategy change just prior to the launch of Voodoo3 by purchasing STB Systems for US$141 million on December 14, 1998.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] STB Systems was one of the larger graphics card manufacturers at the time; the intent was for 3dfx to start manufacturing, marketing, and selling its own graphics cards, rather than functioning only as an OEM supplier.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Purchase of STB was intended to give 3dfx access to that company's considerable OEM resources and sales channels, but the intended benefits of the acquisition never materialized.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The two corporations were vastly different entities, with different cultures and structures, and they never integrated smoothly.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] STB prior to the 3dfx acquisition also approached Nvidia as a potential partner to acquire the company.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] At the time, STB was Nvidia's largest customer and was only minimally engaged with 3dfx.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx management mistakenly believed that acquiring STB would ensure OEM design wins with their products and that product limitations would be overcome with STB's knowledge in supporting the OEM sales/design win cycles.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Nvidia decided not to acquire STB and to continue to support many brands of graphics board manufacturers.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] After STB was acquired by 3dfx, Nvidia focused on being a virtual graphics card manufacturer for the OEMs and strengthened its position in selling finished reference designs ready for market to the OEMs.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] STB's manufacturing facility in Juarez, Mexico was not able to compete from either a cost or quality point of view when compared to the burgeoning original design manufacturers (ODMs) and Contract electronic manufacturers (CEMs) that were delivering solutions in Asia for Nvidia.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Prior to the STB merger finalizing, some of 3dfx's OEMs warned the company that any product from Juarez will not be deemed fit to ship with their systems, however 3dfx management believed these problems could be addressed over time.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Those customers generally became Nvidia customers and no longer chose to ship 3dfx products.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The acquisition of STB was one of the main contributors to 3dfx's downfall; the Voodoo 3 became the first 3dfx card to be developed in-house rather than by third-party manufacturers, which were a significant source of revenue for the company.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] These third-party manufacturers turned into competitors and began sourcing graphics chips from Nvidia.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] This also further alienated 3dfx's remaining OEM customers, as they had a single source for 3dfx products and could not choose an OEM to provide cost flexibility.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] With the purchase of STB, 3dfx created two cards targeting the low-end market, the Velocity 100, which has 8 MB of SDRAM, and the Velocity 200, which has 16 MB of SGRAM.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The cards both used a chipset based on the Voodoo3 2000, and it was claimed that they were "underclocked".
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] As 3dfx focused more on the retail graphics card space, further inroads into the OEM space were limited.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] A significant requirement of the OEM business was the ability to consistently produce new products on the six-month product refresh cycle the computer manufacturers required; 3dfx did not have the methodology nor the mindset to focus on this business model.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] In the end, 3dfx opted to be a retail distribution company manufacturing their own branded products.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The company's final product was code-named Napalm.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Originally, this was just a Voodoo3 modified to support newer technologies and higher clock speeds, with performance estimated to be around the level of the RIVA TNT2.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] However, Napalm was delayed, and in the meantime Nvidia brought out their landmark GeForce 256 chip, which shifted even more of the computational work from the CPU to the graphics chip.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Napalm would have been unable to compete with the GeForce, so it was redesigned to support multiple chip configurations, like the Voodoo2 had.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The end-product was named VSA-100, with VSA standing for Voodoo Scalable Architecture.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx was finally able to have a product that could defeat the GeForce.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] However, by the time the VSA-100 based cards made it to the market, the GeForce 2 and ATI Radeon cards had arrived and were offering higher performance for the same price.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The only real advantage the Voodoo 5 5500 had over the GeForce 2 GTS or Radeon was its superior spatial anti-aliasing implementation, and the fact that, relative to its peers, it did not suffer such a large performance hit when anti-aliasing was enabled.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx was fully aware of the Voodoo 5's speed deficiency, so they touted it as quality over speed, which was a reversal of the Voodoo 3 marketing which emphasized raw performance over features.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 5500 sales were respectable but volumes were not at a level to keep 3dfx afloat.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] On March 28, 2000, 3dfx bought GigaPixel for US$186 million, in order to help launch its Rampage product to market quicker.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] GigaPixel had previously almost won the contract to build Microsoft's Xbox console, but lost out to Nvidia.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] However, in late 2000, not long after the launch of the Voodoo 4, several of 3dfx's creditors decided to initiate bankruptcy proceedings.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] 3dfx, as a whole, would have had virtually no chance of successfully contesting these proceedings, and instead opted to sell its assets to Nvidia, effectively ceasing to exist as a company.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The resolution and legality of those arrangements (with respect to the purchase, 3dfx's creditors and its bankruptcy proceedings) took over a decade to resolve in the federal courts.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Specifically, the trustee of 3dfx's bankruptcy estate challenged 3dfx's sale of its assets to Nvidia as an allegedly fraudulent conveyance.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] On November 6, 2014, in an unpublished memorandum order, the U.S.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit affirmed the "district court's judgment affirming the bankruptcy court's determination that [Nvidia] did not pay less than fair market value for assets purchased from 3dfx shortly before 3dfx filed for bankruptcy".
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] A majority of the engineering and design team working on Rampage/Sage who remained with the transition, were requested and remained in house to work on what became the GeForce FX series.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Others accepted employment with ATI to bring their knowledge to the creation of the X series of video cards and the development of Crossfire, their own version of SLI.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The prototype Spectre 1000 cards were delivered to software developers mere days before declaring insolvency.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The software team developed both device drivers and a binary-compatible soft emulation of the Rampage function set.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Thus, there were working Windows NT device drivers within a few days of the power on of the Rampage system on the 2nd week of December, 2000.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] At the time of Nvidia's acquisition, 3dfx had already been developing the successors to Spectre.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] "Fear", based on a next-generation Rampage called Fusion, and Sage2.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] "Mojo" would combine both into a single die, implement tiled rendering, and showcase some advanced technologies from the GigaPixel acquisition.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The unreleased Spectre 1000 card, based on Rampage, would eventually be leaked and tested.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Performance indicated that it would have struggled to compete with Nvidia's already-released GeForce 256, though the proposed Spectre 2000 and Spectre 3000 cards, which featured a combination of Rampage and Sage units, would have led the market until late 2002, with Nvidia's GeForce 4 series.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] After Nvidia acquired 3dfx's intellectual property, they announced that they would not provide technical support for 3dfx products.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] As of 2019, drivers and support are still offered by community websites.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] However, while functional, the drivers do not carry a manufacturer's backing and are considered beta software.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] For a limited time, Nvidia offered a program under which 3dfx owners could trade in their cards for Nvidia cards of similar performance.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] On December 15, 2000, 3dfx apologized to the customers with a final press release.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] In 2003, the source code for 3dfx drivers leaked, resulting in fan-made, updated drivers and further support.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Although 1997 was marked by analysts as a turning point for 3dfx due to the marketing led by the new CEO Greg Ballard, there was criticism of Ballard's understanding of R&D in the graphics industry.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Then 3dfx released word in early 1999 that the still-competitive Voodoo2 would support only OpenGL and Glide under Microsoft's Windows 2000 operating system, and not Direct3D.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Many games were transitioning to Direct3D at this point, and the announcement caused many PC gamers – the core demographic of 3dfx's market – to switch to Nvidia or ATI offerings for their new machines.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Ballard resigned shortly after, in January 2000.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] A typical Voodoo Graphics PCI expansion card consisted of a DAC, a frame buffer processor and a texture mapping unit, along with 4 MB of EDO DRAM.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The RAM and graphics processors operated at 50 MHz.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] It provided only 3D acceleration and as such the computer also needed a traditional video controller for conventional 2D software.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] A pass-through VGA cable daisy-chained the video controller to the Voodoo, which was itself connected to the monitor.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The method used to engage the Voodoo's output circuitry varied between cards, with some using mechanical relays while others utilized purely solid-state components.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The mechanical relays emitted an audible "clicking" sound when they engaged and disengaged.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] In August 1997, 3dfx released the **Voodoo Rush** chipset, combining a Voodoo chip with a 2D chip that lay on the same circuit board, eliminating the need for a separate VGA card.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Most cards were built with an Alliance Semiconductor AT25/AT3D 2D component, but there were some built with a Macronix chip and there were initial plans to partner with Trident but no such boards were ever marketed.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Rush had the same specifications as Voodoo Graphics, but did not perform as well because the Rush chipset had to share memory bandwidth with the CRTC of the 2D chip.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Furthermore, the Rush chipset was not directly present on the PCI bus but had to be programmed through linked registers of the 2D chip.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Like the Voodoo Graphics, there was no interrupt mechanism, so the driver had to poll the Rush in order to determine whether a command had completed or not; the indirection through the 2D component added significant overhead here and tended to back up traffic on the PCI interface.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The typical performance hit was around 10% compared to Voodoo Graphics, and even worse in windowed mode.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Later, Rush boards were released by Hercules featuring 8 MiB VRAM and a 10% higher clock speed, in an attempt to close this performance gap.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Some manufacturers bundled a PC version of Atari Games' racing game *San Francisco Rush*, the arcade version of which utilised a slightly upgraded Voodoo Graphics chipset with an extra texture mapping unit and additional texture memory.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Voodoo Rush was 3dfx's first commercial failure.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Sales were very poor, and the cards were discontinued within a year.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The 3dfx Voodoo2, the successor to the Voodoo Graphics chipset released in March 1998, was architecturally similar, but the basic board configuration added a second texturing unit, allowing two textures to be drawn in a single pass.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Voodoo2 required three chips and a separate VGA graphics card, whereas new competing 3D products, such as the ATI Rage Pro, Nvidia RIVA 128, and Rendition Verite 2200, were single-chip products.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Despite some shortcomings, such as the card's dithered 16-bit 3D color rendering and 800x600 resolution limitations, no other manufacturers' products could match the smooth framerates that the Voodoo2 produced.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] It was a landmark (and expensive) achievement in PC 3D-graphics.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Its excellent performance, and the mindshare gained from the original Voodoo Graphics, resulted in its success.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Many users even preferred Voodoo2's dedicated purpose, because they were free to use the quality 2D card of their choice as a result.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Some 2D/3D combined solutions at the time offered quite sub-par 2D quality and speed.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Voodoo2 introduced Scan-Line Interleave (SLI), in which two Voodoo2 boards were connected together, each drawing half the scan lines of the screen.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] SLI increased the maximum resolution supported to 1024×768.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Because of the high cost and inconvenience of using three separate graphics cards (two Voodoo2 SLI plus the general purpose 2D graphics adapter), the Voodoo2 SLI scheme had minimal effect on total market share and was not a financial success.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] SLI capability was not offered in subsequent 3dfx board designs, although the technology would be later used to link the VSA-100 chips on the Voodoo 5.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The arrival of the Nvidia RIVA TNT with integrated 2D/3D chipset would offer minor challenge to the Voodoo2's supremacy months later.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Near the end of 1998, 3dfx released the **Voodoo Banshee**, which featured a lower price achieved through higher component integration, and a more complete feature-set including 2D acceleration, to target the mainstream consumer market.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] A single-chip solution, the Banshee was a combination of a 2D video card and partial (only one texture mapping unit) Voodoo2 3D hardware.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Due to the missing second TMU, in 3D scenes which used multiple textures per polygon, the Voodoo2 was significantly faster.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] However, in scenes dominated by single-textured polygons, the Banshee could match or exceed the Voodoo2 due to its higher clock speed and resulting greater pixel fillrate.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Banshee's 2D acceleration was the first such hardware from 3dfx and it was very capable.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] It rivaled the fastest 2D cores from Matrox, Nvidia, and ATI.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] It consisted of a 128-bit 2D GUI engine and a 128-bit VESA VBE 3.0 VGA core.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The graphics chip capably accelerated DirectDraw and supported all of the Windows Graphics Device Interface (GDI) in hardware, with all 256 raster operations and tertiary functions, and hardware polygon acceleration.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The 2D core achieved near-theoretical maximum performance with a null driver test in Windows NT.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Voodoo Banshee supports MPEG2 video acceleration.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Voodoo 3 was hyped as the graphics card that would make 3dfx the undisputed leader, but the actual product was below expectations.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Though it was still the fastest as it edged the RIVA TNT2 by a small margin, the Voodoo3 lacked 32-bit color and large texture support.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Though at that time few games supported large textures and 32-bit color, and those that did generally were too demanding to be run at playable framerates, the features "32-bit color support" and "2048×2048 textures" were much more impressive on paper than 16-bit color and 256×256 texture support.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Voodoo3 sold relatively well, but was disappointing compared to the first two models and 3dfx lost the market leadership to Nvidia.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] As 3dfx attempted to counter the TNT2 threat, it was surprised by Nvidia's GeForce 256.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The GeForce was a single-chip processor with integrated transform, lighting, triangle setup/clipping (hardware T&L), and rendering engines, giving it a significant performance advantage over the Voodoo3.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The 3dfx Voodoo3 2000 PCI was the highest-performance 2D/3D card available for the Apple Macintosh at the time of its release, though support from 3dfx was labeled as 'beta' and required a firmware reflash.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] As game developers switched to DirectX and OpenGL, which respectively had become the industry standard and were becoming increasingly popular, 3dfx released its Glide API under the General Public License on December 6, 1999.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Voodoo 5 5000, which had 32 MB of VRAM to the 5500's 64 MB, was never launched.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The only other member of the Voodoo 5 line, the Voodoo 4 4500, was as much of a disaster as Voodoo Rush, because it had performance well short of its value-oriented peers combined with a late launch.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Voodoo 4 was beaten in almost all areas by the GeForce 2 MX—a low-cost board sold mostly as an OEM part for computer manufacturers—and the Radeon VE.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] One unusual trait of the Voodoo 4 and 5 was that the Macintosh versions of these cards had both VGA and DVI output jacks, whereas the PC versions had only the VGA connector.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Also, the Mac versions of the Voodoo 4 and 5 had a weakness in that they did not support hardware-based MPEG2 decode acceleration, which hindered the playback of DVDs on a Mac equipped with a Voodoo graphics card.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] The Voodoo 5 6000 never made it to market, due to a severe bug resulting in data corruption on the AGP bus on certain boards, and was limited to AGP 2x.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] It was thus incompatible with the new Pentium 4 motherboards.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Only a few more than one thousand units of the graphics card were ever produced.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] Later tests proved that the Voodoo 5 6000 outperformed not only the GeForce 2 GTS and ATI Radeon 7200, but also the faster GeForce 2 Ultra and Radeon 7500.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] In some cases it was shown to compete well with the GeForce 3, trading performance places with the card on various tests.
[src:desktop-computer/3dfx] However, the prohibitively high production cost of the card, particularly the 4 chip setup, external power supply and 128 MB of VRAM (which would have made it the first consumer card with that amount of memory), would have likely hampered its competitiveness.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] While 2G networks such as GPRS and EDGE supported limited data services, 3G introduced significantly higher-speed mobile internet and enhanced multimedia capabilities, in addition to improved voice quality.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] It provided moderate internet speeds suitable for general web browsing and multimedia content including video calling and mobile TV, supporting services that provide an information transfer rate of at least 144 kbit/s.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Later 3G releases, often referred to as 3.5G (HSPA) and 3.75G (HSPA+) as well as EV-DO, introduced important improvements, enabling 3G networks to offer mobile broadband access with speeds ranging from several Mbit/s up to 42 Mbit/s.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] These updates improved the reliability and speed of internet browsing, video streaming, and online gaming, enhancing the overall user experience for smartphones and mobile modems in comparison to earlier 3G technologies.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] 3G was later succeeded by 4G technology, which provided even higher data transfer rates and introduced advancements in network performance.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] A new generation of cellular standards has emerged roughly every decade since the introduction of 1G systems in 1979.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Each generation is defined by the introduction of new frequency bands, higher data rates, and transmission technologies that are not backward-compatible due to the need for significant changes in network architecture and infrastructure.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Several telecommunications companies marketed wireless mobile Internet services as *3G*, indicating that the advertised service was provided over a 3G wireless network.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] However, 3G services have largely been supplanted in marketing by 4G and 5G services in most areas of the world.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Services advertised as 3G are required to meet IMT-2000 technical standards, including standards for reliability and speed (data transfer rates).
[src:desktop-computer/3g] To meet the IMT-2000 standards, Third-generation mobile networks, or 3G, must maintain minimum consistent Internet speeds of 144 Kbps.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] However, many services advertised as 3G provide higher speed than the minimum technical requirements for a 3G service.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Subsequent 3G releases, denoted 3.5G and 3.75G, provided mobile broadband access of several Mbit/s for smartphones and mobile modems in laptop computers.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The 3G systems and radio interfaces are based on spread spectrum radio transmission technology.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] While the GSM EDGE standard ("2.9G"), DECT cordless phones and Mobile WiMAX standards formally also fulfill the IMT-2000 requirements and are approved as 3G standards by ITU, these are typically not branded as 3G and are based on completely different technologies.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] While DECT cordless phones and Mobile WiMAX standards formally also fulfill the IMT-2000 requirements, they are not usually considered due to their rarity and unsuitability for usage with mobile phones.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The 3G (UMTS and CDMA2000) research and development projects started in 1992.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In 1999, ITU approved five radio interfaces for IMT-2000 as a part of the ITU-R M.1457 Recommendation; WiMAX was added in 2007.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] There are evolutionary standards (EDGE and CDMA) that are backward-compatible extensions to pre-existing 2G networks as well as revolutionary standards that require all-new network hardware and frequency allocations.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The cell phones use UMTS in combination with 2G GSM standards and bandwidths, but *do not support EDGE*.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The latter group is the UMTS family, which consists of standards developed for IMT-2000, as well as the independently developed standards DECT and WiMAX, which were included because they fit the IMT-2000 definition.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] While EDGE fulfills the 3G specifications, most GSM/UMTS phones report EDGE ("2.75G") and UMTS ("3G") functionality.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] 3G technology was the result of research and development work carried out by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) in the early 1980s.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] 3G specifications and standards were developed in fifteen years.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The technical specifications were made available to the public under the name IMT-2000.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The communication spectrum between 400 MHz to 3 GHz was allocated for 3G.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Both the government and communication companies approved the 3G standard.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The first pre-commercial 3G network was launched by NTT DoCoMo in Japan in 1998, branded as FOMA.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] It was first available in May 2001 as a pre-release (test) of W-CDMA technology.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The first commercial launch of 3G was also by NTT DoCoMo in Japan on 1 October 2001, although it was initially somewhat limited in scope; broader availability of the system was delayed by apparent concerns over its reliability.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The first network to go commercially live was by SK Telecom in South Korea on the CDMA-based 1xEV-DO technology in January 2002.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] By May 2002, the second South Korean 3G network was by KT on EV-DO and thus the South Koreans were the first to see competition among 3G operators.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The first commercial United States 3G network was by Monet Mobile Networks, on CDMA2000 1x EV-DO technology, but the network provider later shut down operations.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The second 3G network operator in the US was Verizon Wireless in July 2002, also on CDMA2000 1x EV-DO.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] AT&T Mobility was also a true 3G UMTS network, having completed its upgrade of the 3G network to HSUPA.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The first commercial United Kingdom 3G network was started by Hutchison Telecom which was originally behind Orange S.A.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In 2003, it announced first commercial third generation or 3G mobile phone network in the UK.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The first pre-commercial demonstration network in the southern hemisphere was built in Adelaide, South Australia, by m.Net Corporation in February 2002 using UMTS on 2100 MHz.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] This was a demonstration network for the 2002 IT World Congress.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The first commercial 3G network was launched by Hutchison Telecommunications branded as *Three* or "3" in June 2003.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In India, on 11 December 2008, the first 3G mobile and internet services were launched by a state-owned company, Mahanagar Telecom Nigam Limited (MTNL), within the metropolitan cities of Delhi and Mumbai.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] After MTNL, another state-owned company, Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited (BSNL), began deploying the 3G networks country-wide.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Emtel launched the first 3G network in Africa.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Japan was one of the first countries to adopt 3G, the reason being the process of 3G spectrum allocation, which in Japan was awarded without much upfront cost.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The frequency spectrum was allocated in the US and Europe based on auctioning, thereby requiring a huge initial investment for any company wishing to provide 3G services.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] European companies collectively paid over 100 billion dollars in their spectrum auctions.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Nepal Telecom adopted 3G Service for the first time in southern Asia.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] However, its 3G was relatively slow to be adopted in Nepal.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In some instances, 3G networks do not use the same radio frequencies as 2G, so mobile operators must build entirely new networks and license entirely new frequencies, especially to achieve high data transmission rates.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Other countries' delays were due to the expenses of upgrading transmission hardware, especially for UMTS, whose deployment required the replacement of most broadcast towers.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Due to these issues and difficulties with deployment, many carriers could not or delayed the acquisition of these updated capabilities.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In December 2007, 190 3G networks were operating in 40 countries and 154 HSDPA networks were operating in 71 countries, according to the Global Mobile Suppliers Association (GSA).
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In Asia, Europe, Canada, and the US, telecommunication companies use W-CDMA technology with the support of around 100 terminal designs to operate 3G mobile networks.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The roll-out of 3G networks was delayed by the enormous costs of additional spectrum licensing fees in some countries.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The license fees in some European countries were particularly high, bolstered by government auctions of a limited number of licenses and sealed bid auctions, and initial excitement over 3G's potential.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] This led to a telecoms crash that ran concurrently with similar crashes in the fibre-optic and dot.com fields.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The 3G standard is perhaps well known because of a massive expansion of the mobile communications market post-2G and advances of the consumer mobile phone.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] An especially notable development during this time is the smartphone (for example, the iPhone, and the Android family), combining the abilities of a PDA with a mobile phone, leading to widespread demand for mobile internet connectivity.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] 3G has also introduced the term "mobile broadband" because its speed and capability made it a viable alternative for internet browsing, and USB Modems connecting to 3G networks, and now 4G became increasingly common.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] By June 2007, the 200 millionth 3G subscriber had been connected of which 10 million were in Nepal and 8.2 million in India.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] This 200 millionth is only 6.7% of the 3 billion mobile phone subscriptions worldwide.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In Europe the leading country for 3G penetration is Italy with a third of its subscribers migrated to 3G.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Other leading countries for 3G use include Nepal, UK, Austria, Australia and Singapore at the 32% migration level.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] According to ITU estimates, as of Q4 2012 there were 2096 million active mobile-broadband subscribers worldwide out of a total of 6835 million subscribers—this is just over 30%.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] About half the mobile-broadband subscriptions are for subscribers in developed nations, 934 million out of 1600 million total, well over 50%.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In Japan, 3G penetration was similar at about 81%, but smart phone ownership was lower at about 17%.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In China, there were 486.5 million 3G subscribers in June 2014, in a population of 1,385,566,537 (2013 UN estimate).
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Since the increasing adoption of 4G networks across the globe, 3G use has been in decline.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Several operators around the world have already or are in the process of shutting down their 3G networks (see table below).
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In several places, 3G is being shut down while its older predecessor 2G is being kept in operation; Vodafone UK is doing this, citing 2G's usefulness as a low-power fallback.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] EE in the UK, plans to switch off their 3G networks in early 2024.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In the US, Verizon shutdown their 3G services on 31 December 2022, T-Mobile shut down Sprint's networks on 31 March 2022 and shutdown their main networks on 1 July 2022, and AT&T has done so on 22 February 2022.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] According to Telenor IoT, 3G sunsets outpace 2G in Europe, where 19 operators in 14 countries plan to phase out 3G by 2025.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Only 8 operators in 8 nations are scheduled to shut down their 2G networks by the same year however.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Currently 3G around the world is declining in availability and support.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Technology that depends on 3G for usage are becoming inoperable in many places.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] For example, the European Union plans to ensure that member countries maintain 2G networks as a fallback, so 3G devices that are backwards compatible with 2G frequencies can continue to be used.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] However, in countries that plan to decommission 2G networks or have already done so as well, such as the United States and Singapore, devices supporting only 3G and backwards compatible with 2G are becoming inoperable.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] As of February 2022, less than 1% of cell phone customers in the United States used 3G; AT&T offered free replacement devices to some customers in the run-up to its shutdown.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] It has been estimated that there are almost 8,000 patents declared essential (FRAND) related to the 483 technical specifications which form the 3GPP and 3GPP2 standards.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Twelve companies accounted in 2004 for 90% of the patents (Qualcomm, Ericsson, Nokia, Motorola, Philips, NTT DoCoMo, Siemens, Mitsubishi, Fujitsu, Hitachi, InterDigital, and Matsushita).
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Even then, some patents essential to 3G might not have been declared by their patent holders.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] It is believed that Nortel and Lucent have undisclosed patents essential to these standards.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Furthermore, the existing 3G Patent Platform Partnership Patent pool has little impact on FRAND protection because it excludes the four largest patent owners for 3G.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] ITU has not provided a clear definition of the data rate that users can expect from 3G equipment or providers.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Thus users sold 3G service may not be able to point to a standard and say that the rates it specifies are not being met.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] 3G networks offer greater security than their 2G predecessors.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] By allowing the UE (User Equipment) to authenticate the network it is attaching to, the user can be sure the network is the intended one and not an impersonator.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] 3G networks use the KASUMI block cipher instead of the older A5/1 stream cipher.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] However, a number of serious weaknesses in the KASUMI cipher have been identified.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] In addition to the 3G network infrastructure security, end-to-end security is offered when application frameworks such as IMS are accessed, although this is not strictly a 3G property.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] The bandwidth and location capabilities introduced by 3G networks enabled a wide range of applications that were previously impractical or unavailable on 2G networks.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Among the most significant advancements was the ability to perform data-intensive tasks, such as browsing the internet seamlessly while on the move, as well as engaging in other activities that benefited from faster data speeds and enhanced reliability.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Beyond personal communication, 3G networks supported applications in various fields, including medical devices, fire alarms, and ankle monitors.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] This versatility marked a significant milestone in cellular communications, as 3G became the first network to enable such a broad range of use cases.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] By expanding its functionality beyond traditional mobile phone usage, 3G set the stage for the integration of cellular networks into a wide array of technologies and services, paving the way for further advancements with subsequent generations of mobile networks.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] Both 3GPP and 3GPP2 are working on the extensions to 3G standards that are based on an all-IP network infrastructure and using advanced wireless technologies such as MIMO.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] These specifications already display features characteristic for IMT-Advanced (4G), the successor of 3G.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] However, falling short of the bandwidth requirements for 4G (which is 1 Gbit/s for stationary and 100 Mbit/s for mobile operation), these standards are classified as 3.9G or Pre-4G.
[src:desktop-computer/3g] 3GPP plans to meet the 4G goals with LTE Advanced, whereas Qualcomm has halted UMB development in favour of the LTE family.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD's main products include microprocessors, embedded processors, and graphics processors for servers, workstations, PCs, and embedded system applications, as well as chipsets for motherboards.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The company has also expanded into new markets, such as data centers, gaming, and high-performance computing.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD's processors are used in a wide range of computing devices, including PCs, servers, laptops, and gaming consoles.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Initially manufacturing its own processors, the company outsourced its manufacturing after GlobalFoundries was spun off in 2009.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Through its Xilinx acquisition in 2022, AMD offers field-programmable gate array (FPGA) products.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD was founded in 1969 by Jerry Sanders and a group of his fellow Fairchild Semiconductor colleagues.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The company's early products were primarily memory chips and other computer components.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In 1975, AMD entered the microprocessor market, competing with Intel, its main rival in the industry.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In the early 2000s, it experienced significant growth and success, partly due to its strong position in the PC market and its Athlon and Opteron processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The company faced challenges in the late 2000s and early 2010s, as it struggled to compete with Intel.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In the late 2010s, AMD regained market share by pursuing a penetration pricing strategy for its Ryzen processors, offering a competitive performance and lower costs than Intel microprocessors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In 2022, AMD surpassed Intel by market capitalization for the first time.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Advanced Micro Devices was formally incorporated by Jerry Sanders, along with seven of his colleagues from Fairchild Semiconductor—Ed Turney; John Carey; Sven Simonsen; Jack Gifford, and three members of his team: Frank Botte, Jim Giles, and Larry Stenger, on May 1, 1969.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Sanders, an electrical engineer who was the director of marketing at Fairchild, had, like many of its executives, grown frustrated with the increasing lack of support, opportunity, and flexibility within the company.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] He later decided to leave to start his own semiconductor company, following the footsteps of Robert Noyce (developer of the first silicon integrated circuit at Fairchild in 1959) and Gordon Moore, who together founded the semiconductor company Intel in July 1968.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In September 1969, AMD moved from its temporary location in Santa Clara to its new $500,000 15,000sqft headquarters at 901 Thompson Place, Sunnyvale, which housed the entire company, including the 8-mask, 7 μm feature size, 2-inch diameter wafer production.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] To immediately secure a customer base, AMD initially became a second source supplier of microchips designed by Fairchild (the 5 V TTL "9300" logic series) and National Semiconductor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD first focused on producing logic chips.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In November 1969, the company manufactured its first product: the Am9300, a 4-bit MSI shift register, which began selling in 1970.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Also in 1970, AMD produced its first proprietary product, the Am2501 logic counter, which was highly successful.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Its bestselling product in 1971 was the Am2505, the fastest multiplier available.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In 1971, AMD entered the RAM chip market, beginning with the Am3101, a 64-bit bipolar RAM.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] That year AMD also greatly increased the sales volume of its linear integrated circuits, and by year-end the company's total annual sales reached US$4.6 million.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The company was a second source for Intel MOS/LSI circuits by 1973, with products such as Am14/1506 and Am14/1507, dual 100-bit dynamic shift registers.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] By 1975, AMD was producing 212 products – of which 49 were proprietary, including the Am9102 (a static N-channel 1024-bit RAM) and three low-power Schottky MSI circuits: Am25LS07, Am25LS08, and Am25LS09.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Intel had created the first microprocessor, its 4-bit 4004, in 1971.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] By 1975, AMD entered the microprocessor market with the Am9080, a reverse-engineered clone of the Intel 8080, and the Am2900 bit-slice microprocessor family.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] When Intel began installing microcode in its microprocessors in 1976, it entered into a cross-licensing agreement with AMD, which was granted a copyright license to the microcode in its microprocessors and peripherals, effective October 1976.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In 1977, AMD entered into a joint venture with Siemens, a German engineering conglomerate wishing to enhance its technology expertise and enter the American market.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Siemens purchased 20% of AMD's stock, giving the company an infusion of cash to increase its product lines.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The two companies also jointly established Advanced Micro Computers (AMC), located in Silicon Valley and in Germany, allowing AMD to enter the microcomputer development and manufacturing field, in particular based on AMD's second-source Zilog Z8000 microprocessors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] When the two companies' vision for Advanced Micro Computers diverged, AMD bought out Siemens' stake in the American division in 1979.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD closed Advanced Micro Computers in late 1981 after switching focus to manufacturing second-source Intel x86 microprocessors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Total sales in fiscal year 1978 topped $100 million, and in 1979, AMD debuted on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In 1979, production also began on AMD's new semiconductor fabrication plant in Austin, Texas; the company already had overseas assembly facilities in Penang and Manila, and began construction on a fabrication plant in San Antonio in 1981.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In 1980, AMD began supplying semiconductor products for telecommunications, an industry undergoing rapid expansion and innovation.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Intel had introduced the first x86 microprocessors in 1978.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In 1981, IBM created its personal computer, and wanted Intel's x86 processors, but only under the condition that Intel would also provide a second-source manufacturer for its patented x86 microprocessors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Intel and AMD entered into a 10-year technology exchange agreement, first signed in October 1981 and formally executed in February 1982.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The technical information and licenses needed to make and sell a part would be exchanged for a royalty to the developing company.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The 1982 agreement also extended the 1976 AMD–Intel cross-licensing agreement through 1995.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The agreement included the right to invoke arbitration of disagreements, and after five years the right of either party to end the agreement with one year's notice.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The main result of the 1982 agreement was that AMD became a second-source manufacturer of Intel's x86 microprocessors and related chips, and Intel provided AMD with database tapes for its 8086, 80186, and 80286 chips.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] However, in the event of a bankruptcy or takeover of AMD, the cross-licensing agreement would be effectively canceled.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Beginning in 1982, AMD began volume-producing second-source Intel-licensed 8086, 8088, 80186, and 80188 processors, and by 1984, its own Am286 clone of Intel's 80286 processor, for the rapidly growing market of IBM PCs and IBM clones.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] It also continued its successful concentration on proprietary bipolar chips.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The company continued to spend greatly on research and development, and created the world's first 512K EPROM in 1984.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] That year, AMD was listed in the book *The 100 Best Companies to Work for in America*, and later made the *Fortune* 500 list for the first time in 1985.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] By mid-1985, the microchip market experienced a severe downturn, mainly due to long-term aggressive trade practices (dumping) from Japan, but also due to a crowded and non-innovative chip market in the United States.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] During this time, AMD withdrew from the DRAM market, and made some headway into the CMOS market, which it had lagged in entering, having focused instead on bipolar chips.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD had some success in the mid-1980s with the AMD7910 and AMD7911 "World Chip" FSK modem, one of the first multi-standard devices that covered both Bell and CCITT tones at up to 1200 baud half duplex or 300/300 full duplex.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Beginning in 1986, AMD embraced the perceived shift toward RISC with its own AMD Am29000 (29k) processor; the 29k survived as an embedded processor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The company also increased its EPROM memory market share in the late 1980s.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Throughout the 1980s, AMD was a second-source supplier of Intel x86 processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In 1991, it introduced its 386-compatible Am386, an AMD-designed chip.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Creating its own chips, AMD began to compete directly with Intel.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In January 1996, AMD acquired NexGen for $857 million to develop what eventually became AMD K6.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] At the time, NexGen was working on its Nx686 microprocessor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD had a large, successful flash memory business, even during the dotcom bust.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In December 2005, AMD divested itself of Spansion to focus on the microprocessor market, and Spansion went public in an IPO.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] On July 24, 2006, AMD announced its acquisition of the Canadian 3D graphics card company ATI Technologies.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD paid $4.3 billion and 58 million shares of its capital stock, for approximately $5.4 billion.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The transaction was completed on October 25, 2006.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] On August 30, 2010, AMD announced that it would retire the ATI brand name for its graphics chipsets in favor of the AMD brand name.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In October 2008, AMD announced plans to spin off manufacturing operations in the form of GlobalFoundries Inc., a multibillion-dollar joint venture with Advanced Technology Investment Co., an investment company formed by the government of Abu Dhabi.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The partnership and spin-off gave AMD an infusion of cash and allowed it to focus solely on chip design.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] To assure the Abu Dhabi investors of the new venture's success, AMD's CEO Hector Ruiz stepped down in July 2008, while remaining executive chairman, in preparation for becoming chairman of GlobalFoundries in March 2009.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] President and COO Dirk Meyer became AMD's CEO.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Recessionary losses necessitated AMD cutting 1,100 jobs in 2009.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In August 2011, AMD announced that former Lenovo executive Rory Read would be joining the company as CEO, replacing Meyer.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In November 2011, AMD announced plans to lay off more than 10% (1,400) of its employees from across all divisions worldwide.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In October 2012, it announced plans to lay off an additional 15% of its workforce to reduce costs in the face of declining sales revenue.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The inclusion of AMD chips into the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One were later seen as saving AMD from bankruptcy.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD acquired the low-power server manufacturer SeaMicro in early 2012, with an eye to bringing out an Arm64 server chip.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] On October 8, 2014, AMD announced that Rory Read had stepped down after three years as president and chief executive officer.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] He was succeeded by Lisa Su, a key lieutenant who had been chief operating officer since June.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] On October 16, 2014, AMD announced a new restructuring plan along with its Q3 results.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] As part of this restructuring, AMD announced that 7% of its global workforce would be laid off by the end of 2014.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] After the GlobalFoundries spin-off and subsequent layoffs, AMD was left with significant vacant space at 1 AMD Place, its aging Sunnyvale headquarters office complex.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In August 2016, AMD's 47 years in Sunnyvale came to a close when it signed a lease with the Irvine Company for a new 220,000 sq. ft. headquarters building in Santa Clara.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] AMD's new location at Santa Clara Square faces the headquarters of arch-rival Intel across the Bayshore Freeway and San Tomas Aquino Creek.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Around the same time, AMD also agreed to sell 1 AMD Place to the Irvine Company.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In April 2019, the Irvine Company secured approval from the Sunnyvale City Council of its plans to demolish 1 AMD Place and redevelop the entire 32-acre site into townhomes and apartments.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In October 2020, AMD announced that it was acquiring Xilinx, the market leader in field programmable gate arrays and complex programmable logic devices (FPGAs and CPLDs) in an all-stock transaction.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The acquisition was completed in February 2022, with an estimated acquisition price of $50 billion.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In January 2024, AMD announced it was discontinuing the production of all complex programmable logic devices (CPLDs) acquired through Xilinx.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In March 2024, a rally in semiconductor stocks pushed AMD's valuation above $300B for the first time.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In July 2024, AMD announced that it would acquire the Finnish-based artificial intelligence start-up company Silo AI in a $665 million all-cash deal in an attempt to better compete with AI chip market leader Nvidia.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In August 2024, AMD signed a deal to acquire ZT Systems for $4.9 billion.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] The company creates custom computing infrastructure that is used for AI tasks.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Since early 2024, AMD has made significant gains in the server CPU market, reducing the gap with Intel.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] Initial reports of a 50:50 market split drew on incorrect data and were later revised.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] As of July 2025, Intel holds 63.3% of the server CPU market, while AMD has reached 36.5%, showing a strong upward trend for AMD despite Intel's continuing lead.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In June 2025, AMD unveiled the AI server for 2026, the MI400 series of chips, which will be the basis of a new server called "Helios".
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] In October 2025, the company announced it had agreed a deal with OpenAI to sell six gigawatts of its AI processors over the next five years.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p01] As part of the deal, OpenAI has the option to acquire a 10 per cent stake in AMD: 160 million shares at a token price of $0.01 per share contingent on meeting undisclosed performance targets, the final tranche of options requiring AMD common stock to reach $600 per share.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In February 1982, AMD signed a contract with Intel, becoming a licensed second-source manufacturer of 8086 and 8088 processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] IBM wanted to use the Intel 8088 in its IBM PC, but its policy at the time was to require at least two sources for its chips.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD later produced the Am286 under the same arrangement.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 1984, Intel internally decided to no longer cooperate with AMD in supplying product information to shore up its advantage in the marketplace, and delayed and eventually refused to convey the technical details of the Intel 80386.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 1987, AMD invoked arbitration over the issue, and Intel reacted by canceling the 1982 technological-exchange agreement altogether.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] After three years of testimony, AMD eventually won in arbitration in 1992, but Intel disputed this decision.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Another long legal dispute followed, ending in 1994 when the Supreme Court of California sided with the arbitrator and AMD.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 1990, Intel countersued AMD, renegotiating AMD's right to use derivatives of Intel's microcode for its cloned processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In the face of uncertainty during the legal dispute, AMD was forced to develop clean room designed versions of Intel code for its x386 and x486 processors, the former long after Intel had released its own x386 in 1985.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In March 1991, AMD released the Am386, its clone of the Intel 386 processor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] By October of the same year it had sold one million units.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 1993, AMD introduced the first of the Am486 family of processors, which proved popular with a large number of original equipment manufacturers, including Compaq, which signed an exclusive agreement using the Am486.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Am5x86, another Am486-based processor, was released in November 1995, and continued AMD's success as a fast, cost-effective processor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Finally, in an agreement effective 1996, AMD received the rights to the microcode in Intel's x386 and x486 processor families, but not the rights to the microcode in the following generations of processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD's first in-house x86 processor was the K5, launched in 1996.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The "K" in its name was a reference to Kryptonite, the only substance known to harm comic book character Superman.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This itself was a reference to Intel's hegemony over the market, i.e., an anthropomorphization of them as Superman.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The number "5" was a reference to the fifth generation of x86 processors; rival Intel had previously introduced its line of fifth-generation x86 processors as Pentium because the U.S.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Trademark and Patent Office had ruled that mere numbers could not be trademarked.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 1996, AMD purchased NexGen, specifically for the rights to its Nx series of x86-compatible processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD gave the NexGen design team their own building, left them alone, and gave them time and money to rework the Nx686.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The result was the K6 processor, introduced in 1997.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Although it was based on Socket 7, variants such as K6-III/450 were faster than Intel's Pentium II (sixth-generation processor).
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The K7 was AMD's seventh-generation x86 processor, making its debut under the brand name Athlon on June 23, 1999.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Unlike previous AMD processors, it could not be used on the same motherboards as Intel's, due to licensing issues surrounding Intel's Slot 1 connector, and instead used a Slot A connector, referenced to the Alpha processor bus.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Duron was a lower-cost and limited version of the Athlon (64 KB instead of 256 KB L2 cache) in a 462-pin socketed PGA (socket A) or soldered directly onto the motherboard.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Sempron was released as a lower-cost Athlon XP, replacing Duron in the socket A PGA era.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] It has since been migrated upward to all new sockets, up to AM3.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] On October 9, 2001, the Athlon XP was released.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] On February 10, 2003, the Athlon XP with 512 KB L2 Cache was released.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The technology was initially launched as the Opteron server-oriented processor on April 22, 2003.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Shortly thereafter, it was incorporated into a product for desktop PCs, branded Athlon 64.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] On April 21, 2005, AMD released the first dual-core Opteron, an x86-based server CPU.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] A month later, it released the Athlon 64 X2, the first desktop-based dual-core processor family.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In May 2007, AMD abandoned the string "64" in its dual-core desktop product branding, becoming Athlon X2, downplaying the significance of 64-bit computing in its processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Further updates involved improvements to the microarchitecture, and a shift of the target market from mainstream desktop systems to value dual-core desktop systems.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2008, AMD started to release dual-core Sempron processors exclusively in China, branded as the Sempron 2000 series, with lower HyperTransport speed and smaller L2 cache.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD completed its dual-core product portfolio for each market segment.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In September 2007, AMD released the first server Opteron K10 processors, followed in November by the Phenom processor for desktop.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] K10 processors came in dual-core, triple-core, and quad-core versions, with all cores on a single die.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD released a new platform codenamed "Spider", which used the new Phenom processor, and an R770 GPU and a 790 GX/FX chipset from the AMD 700 chipset series.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] However, AMD built the Spider at 65nm, which was uncompetitive with Intel's smaller and more power-efficient 45nm.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In January 2009, AMD released a new processor line dubbed Phenom II, a refresh of the original Phenom built using the 45 nm process.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD's new platform, codenamed "Dragon", used the new Phenom II processor, and an ATI R770 GPU from the R700 GPU family, and a 790 GX/FX chipset from the AMD 700 chipset series.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Phenom II came in dual-core, triple-core and quad-core variants, all using the same die, with cores disabled for the triple-core and dual-core versions.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Phenom II resolved issues that the original Phenom had, including a low clock speed, a small L3 cache, and a Cool'n'Quiet bug that decreased performance.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Phenom II cost less but was not performance-competitive with Intel's mid-to-high-range Core 2 Quads.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Phenom II also enhanced its predecessor's memory controller, allowing it to use DDR3 in a new native socket AM3, while maintaining backward compatibility with AM2+, the socket used for the Phenom, and allowing the use of the DDR2 memory that was used with the platform.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In April 2010, AMD released a new Phenom II Hexa-core (6-core) processor codenamed "Thuban".
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This was a totally new die based on the hexa-core "Istanbul" Opteron processor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] It included AMD's "turbo core" technology, which allows the processor to automatically switch from 6 cores to 3 faster cores when more pure speed is needed.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Magny Cours and Lisbon server parts were released in 2010.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Magny Cours part came in 8 to 12 cores and the Lisbon part in 4 and 6 core parts.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Magny Cours is focused on performance while the Lisbon part is focused on high performance per watt.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Magny Cours is an MCM (multi-chip module) with two hexa-core "Istanbul" Opteron parts.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This will use a new socket G34 for dual and quad-socket processors and thus will be marketed as Opteron 61xx series processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Lisbon uses socket C32 certified for dual-socket use or single socket use only and thus will be marketed as Opteron 41xx processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Both will be built on a 45 nm SOI process.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The initiative intended to move some of the processing originally done on the CPU (e.g. floating-point unit operations) to the GPU, which is better optimized for some calculations.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Fusion was later renamed the AMD APU (Accelerated Processing Unit).
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Llano was AMD's first APU built for laptops.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Llano was the second APU released, targeted at the mainstream market.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] It incorporated a CPU and GPU on the same die, and northbridge functions, and used "Socket FM1" with DDR3 memory.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The CPU part of the processor was based on the Phenom II "Deneb" processor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD suffered an unexpected decrease in revenue based on production problems for the Llano.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] More AMD APUs for laptops running Windows 7 and Windows 8 OS are being used commonly.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] These include AMD's price-point APUs, the E1 and E2, and their mainstream competitors with Intel's Core i-series: The Vision A- series, the A standing for accelerated.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] These range from the lower-performance A4 chipset to the A6, A8, and A10.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] These all incorporate next-generation Radeon graphics cards, with the A4 utilizing the base Radeon HD chip and the rest using a Radeon R4 graphics card, with the exception of the highest-model A10 (A10-7300) which uses an R6 graphics card.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Bulldozer was AMD's microarchitecture codename for server and desktop AMD FX processors, first released on October 12, 2011.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This family 15h microarchitecture is the successor to the family 10h (K10) microarchitecture design.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Bulldozer was a clean-sheet design, not a development of earlier processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The core was specifically aimed at 10–125 W TDP computing products.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD claimed dramatic performance-per-watt efficiency improvements in high-performance computing (HPC) applications with Bulldozer cores.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] While hopes were high that Bulldozer would bring AMD to be performance-competitive with Intel once more, most benchmarks were disappointing.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In some cases the new Bulldozer products were slower than the K10 models they were built to replace.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Piledriver microarchitecture was the 2012 successor to Bulldozer, increasing clock speeds and performance relative to its predecessor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Piledriver would be released in AMD FX, APU, and Opteron product lines.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Piledriver was subsequently followed by the Steamroller microarchitecture in 2013.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Used exclusively in AMD's APUs, Steamroller focused on greater parallelism.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2015, the Excavator microarchitecture replaced Piledriver.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Expected to be the last microarchitecture of the Bulldozer series, Excavator focused on improved power efficiency.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Bobcat microarchitecture was revealed during a speech from Henri Richard, AMD executive vice-president, in Computex 2007, and was put into production during the first quarter of 2011.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Based on the difficulty competing in the x86 market with a single core optimized for the 10–100 W range, AMD had developed a simpler core with a target range of 1–10 watts.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In addition, it was believed that the core could migrate into the hand-held space if the power consumption can be reduced to less than 1 W.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Jaguar is a microarchitecture codename for Bobcat's successor, released in 2013, that is used in various APUs from AMD aimed at the low-power/low-cost market.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Jaguar and its derivates would go on to be used in the custom APUs of the PlayStation 4, Xbox One, PlayStation 4 Pro, Xbox One S, and Xbox One X.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Jaguar would be later followed by the Puma microarchitecture in 2014.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2012, AMD announced it was working on ARM products, both as a semi-custom product and server product.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The initial server product was announced as the Opteron A1100 in 2014, an 8-core Cortex-A57-based ARMv8-A SoC, and was expected to be followed by an APU incorporating a Graphics Core Next GPU.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] However, the Opteron A1100 was not released until 2016, with the delay attributed to adding software support.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The A1100 was also criticized for not having support from major vendors upon its release.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2014, AMD also announced the K12 custom core for release in 2016.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] While being ARMv8-A instruction set architecture compliant, the K12 was expected to be entirely custom-designed, targeting the server, embedded, and semi-custom markets.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] While ARM architecture development continued, products based on K12 were subsequently delayed with no release planned.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Development of AMD's x86-based Zen microarchitecture was preferred.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Zen is an architecture for x86-64 based Ryzen series of CPUs and APUs, introduced in 2017 by AMD and built from the ground up by a team led by Jim Keller, beginning with his arrival in 2012, and taping out before his departure in September 2015.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] One of AMD's primary goals with Zen was an IPC increase of at least 40%, however in February 2017 AMD announced that it had actually achieved a 52% increase.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Processors made on the Zen architecture are built on the 14 nm FinFET node and have a renewed focus on single-core performance and HSA compatibility.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Previous processors from AMD were either built in the 32 nm process ("Bulldozer" and "Piledriver" CPUs) or the 28 nm process ("Steamroller" and "Excavator" APUs).
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Because of this, Zen is much more energy efficient.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Zen architecture is the first to encompass CPUs and APUs from AMD built for a single socket (Socket AM4).
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Also new for this architecture is the implementation of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) technology, something Intel has had for years on some of its processors with its proprietary hyper-threading implementation of SMT.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This is a departure from the "Clustered MultiThreading" design introduced with the Bulldozer architecture.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD released the Zen-based high-end Ryzen 7 "Summit Ridge" series CPUs on March 2, 2017, mid-range Ryzen 5 series CPUs on April 11, 2017, and entry level Ryzen 3 series CPUs on July 27, 2017.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD later released the Epyc line of Zen derived server processors for 1P and 2P systems.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In October 2017, AMD released Zen-based APUs as Ryzen Mobile, incorporating Vega graphics cores.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In January 2018, AMD announced its new lineup plans, with Ryzen 2.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD launched CPUs with the 12nm Zen+ microarchitecture in April 2018, following up with the 7nm Zen 2 microarchitecture in June 2019, including an update to the Epyc line with new processors using the Zen 2 microarchitecture in August 2019, and Zen 3 slated for release in Q3 2020.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] As of 2019, AMD's Ryzen processors were reported to outsell Intel's consumer desktop processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] At CES 2020 AMD announced its Ryzen Mobile 4000, as the first 7 nm x86 mobile processor, the first 7 nm 8-core (also 16-thread) high-performance mobile processor, and the first 8-core (also 16-thread) processor for ultrathin laptops.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This generation is still based on the Zen 2 architecture.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In October 2020, AMD announced new processors based on the Zen 3 architecture.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] On PassMark's Single thread performance test the Ryzen 5 5600x bested all other CPUs besides the Ryzen 9 5950X.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In April 2020, AMD launched three new SKUs which target commercial HPC workloads & hyperconverged infrastructure applications.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The launch was based on Epyc's 7 nm second-generation Rome platform and supported by Dell EMC, Hewlett Packard Enterprise, Lenovo, Supermicro, and Nutanix.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] IBM Cloud was its first public cloud partner.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In August 2022, AMD announced its initial lineup of CPUs based on the new Zen 4 architecture.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Steam Deck, PlayStation 5, Xbox Series X and Series S all use chips based on the Zen 2 microarchitecture, with proprietary tweaks and different configurations in each system's implementation than AMD sells in its own commercially available APUs.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Lee Ka Lau, Francis Lau, Benny Lau, and Kwok Yuen Ho founded ATI in 1985 as Array Technology Incorporated, renamed later Array Technologies Incorporated and finally ATI Technologies.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Working primarily in the OEM field, ATI produced integrated graphics cards for PC manufacturers such as IBM and Commodore.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] By 1987, ATI had grown into an independent graphics-card retailer, introducing EGA Wonder and VGA Wonder card product lines that year.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In the early nineties, they released products able to process graphics without the CPU: in May 1991, the Mach8, in 1992 the Mach32, which offered improved memory bandwidth and GUI acceleration.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] ATI Technologies went public in 1993, with shares listed on NASDAQ and on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 1994, the Mach64 accelerator debuted, powering the Graphics Xpression and Graphics Pro Turbo, offering hardware support for YUV-to-RGB colour space conversion in addition to hardware zoom; early techniques of hardware-based video acceleration.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] ATI introduced its first combination of 2D and 3D accelerator under the name 3D Rage.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This chip was based on the Mach 64, but it featured elemental 3D acceleration.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The ATI Rage line powered almost the entire range of ATI graphics products.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In particular, the Rage Pro was one of the first viable 2D-plus-3D alternatives to 3dfx's 3D-only Voodoo chipset.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] 3D acceleration in the Rage line advanced from the basic functionality within the initial 3D Rage to a more advanced DirectX 6.0 accelerator in 1999 Rage 128.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The All-in-Wonder product line, introduced in 1996, was the first combination of integrated graphics chip with TV tuner card and the first chip that enabled display of computer graphics on a TV set.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The cards featured 3D acceleration powered by ATI's 3D Rage II, 64-bit 2D performance, TV-quality video acceleration, analogue video capture, TV tuner functionality, flicker-free TV-out and stereo TV audio reception.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] ATI entered the mobile computing sector by introducing 3D-graphics acceleration to laptops in 1996.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Mobility product line had to meet requirements different from those of desktop PCs, such as minimized power usage, reduced heat output, TMDS output capabilities for laptop screens, and maximized integration.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 1997, ATI acquired Tseng Labs's graphics assets, which included 40 engineers.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Radeon line of graphics products was unveiled in 2000.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The initial Radeon GPU offered an all-new design with DirectX 7.0 3D acceleration, video acceleration, and 2D acceleration.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Technology developed for a specific Radeon generation could be built in varying levels of features and performance in order to provide products suited for the entire market range, from high-end to budget to mobile versions.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2000, ATI acquired ArtX, which engineered the Flipper graphics chip used in the GameCube video game console.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] They also created a modified version of the chip (codenamed Hollywood) for the successor of the GameCube, the Wii.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Microsoft contracted ATI to design the graphics core (codenamed Xenos) for the Xbox 360.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Later in 2005, ATI acquired Terayon's cable modem silicon intellectual property, strengthening their lead in the consumer digital television market.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Ho remained as chairman of the board until he retired in November 2005.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Dave Orton replaced him as the president and CEO of the organization.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] On July 24, 2006, a joint announcement revealed that AMD would acquire ATI in a deal valued at $5.6 billion.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The acquisition consideration closed on October 25, 2006, and included over $2 billion financed from a loan and 56 million shares of AMD stock.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] ATI's operations became part of the AMD Graphics Product Group (GPG), and ATI's CEO Dave Orton became the executive vice president of Visual and Media Businesses at AMD until his resignation in 2007.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The top-level management was reorganized with the senior vice president and general manager, and the senior vice president and general manager of Consumer Electronics Group, both of whom would report to the CEO of AMD.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] On August 30, 2010, John Trikola announced that AMD would retire the ATI brand for its graphics chipsets in favour of the AMD name.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2007, the ATI division of AMD released the TeraScale microarchitecture implementing a unified shader model.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This design replaced the previous fixed-function hardware of previous graphics cards with multipurpose, programmable shaders.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Initially released as part of the GPU for the Xbox 360, this technology would go on to be used in Radeon branded HD 2000 parts.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Three generations of TeraScale would be designed and used in parts from 2007 to 2015.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In a 2009 restructuring, AMD merged the CPU and GPU divisions to support the company's APUs, which fused both graphics and general purpose processing.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2011, AMD released the successor to TeraScale, Graphics Core Next (GCN).
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This new microarchitecture emphasized GPGPU compute capability in addition to graphics processing, with a particular aim of supporting heterogeneous computing on AMD's APUs.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] GCN's reduced instruction set ISA allowed for significantly increased compute capability over TeraScale's very long instruction word ISA.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Since GCN's introduction with the HD 7970, five generations of the GCN architecture have been produced from 2011 through at least 2018.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In September 2015, AMD separated the graphics technology division of the company into an independent internal unit called the Radeon Technologies Group (RTG), headed by Raja Koduri.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This gave the graphics division of AMD autonomy in product design and marketing.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The RTG then went on to create and release the Polaris and Vega microarchitectures released in 2016 and 2017, respectively.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In particular the Vega, or fifth-generation GCN, microarchitecture includes a number of major revisions to improve performance and compute capabilities.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In November 2017, Raja Koduri left RTG and CEO and President Lisa Su took his position.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In January 2018, it was reported that two industry veterans joined RTG, namely Mike Rayfield as senior vice president and general manager of RTG, and David Wang as senior vice president of engineering for RTG.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In January 2020, AMD announced that its second-generation RDNA graphics architecture was in development, with the aim of competing with the Nvidia RTX graphics products for performance leadership.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In October 2020, AMD announced its new RX 6000 series series GPUs, their first high-end product based on RDNA2 and capable of handling ray-tracing natively, aiming to challenge Nvidia's RTX 3000 GPUs.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2012, AMD's then CEO Rory Read began a program to offer semi-custom designs.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Rather than AMD simply designing and offering a single product, potential customers could work with AMD to design a custom chip based on AMD's intellectual property.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Customers pay a non-recurring engineering fee for design and development, and a purchase price for the resulting semi-custom products.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In particular, AMD noted its unique position of offering both x86 and graphics intellectual property.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] These semi-custom designs would have design wins as the APUs in the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One and the subsequent PlayStation 4 Pro, Xbox One S, Xbox One X, Xbox Series X/S, and PlayStation 5.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Financially, these semi-custom products would represent a majority of the company's revenue in 2016.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In November 2017, AMD and Intel announced that Intel would market a product combining in a single package an Intel Core CPU, a semi-custom AMD Radeon GPU, and HBM2 memory.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Before the launch of Athlon 64 processors in 2003, AMD designed chipsets for its processors spanning the K6 and K7 processor generations.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The chipsets include the AMD-640, AMD-751, and the AMD-761 chipsets.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The situation changed in 2003 with the release of Athlon 64 processors, and AMD chose not to further design its own chipsets for its desktop processors while opening the desktop platform to allow other firms to design chipsets.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This was the "Open Platform Management Architecture" with ATI, VIA and SiS developing its own chipset for Athlon 64 processors and later Athlon 64 X2 and Athlon 64 FX processors, including the Quad FX platform chipset from Nvidia.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The initiative went further with the release of Opteron server processors as AMD stopped the design of server chipsets in 2004 after releasing the AMD-8111 chipset, and again opened the server platform for firms to develop chipsets for Opteron processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] As of today, Nvidia and Broadcom are the sole designing firms of server chipsets for Opteron processors.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] As the company completed the acquisition of ATI Technologies in 2006, the firm gained the ATI design team for chipsets which previously designed the Radeon Xpress 200 and the Radeon Xpress 3200 chipsets.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD then renamed the chipsets for AMD processors under AMD branding (for instance, the CrossFire Xpress 3200 chipset was renamed as AMD 580X CrossFire chipset).
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In February 2007, AMD announced the first AMD-branded chipset since 2004 with the release of the AMD 690G chipset (previously under the development codename *RS690*), targeted at mainstream IGP computing.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] It was the industry's first to implement a HDMI 1.2 port on motherboards, shipping for more than a million units.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] While ATI had aimed at releasing an Intel IGP chipset, the plan was scrapped and the inventories of Radeon Xpress 1250 (codenamed *RS600*, sold under ATI brand) was sold to two OEMs, Abit and ASRock.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Although AMD stated the firm would still produce Intel chipsets, Intel had not granted the license of 1333 MHz FSB to ATI.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] On November 15, 2007, AMD announced a new chipset series portfolio, the AMD 7-Series chipsets, covering from the enthusiast multi-graphics segment to the value IGP segment, to replace the AMD 480/570/580 chipsets and AMD 690 series chipsets, marking AMD's first enthusiast multi-graphics chipset.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Discrete graphics chipsets were launched on November 15, 2007, as part of the codenamed *Spider* desktop platform, and IGP chipsets were launched at a later time in spring 2008 as part of the codenamed *Cartwheel* platform.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD returned to the server chipsets market with the AMD 800S series server chipsets.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] It includes support for up to six SATA 6.0 Gbit/s ports, the C6 power state, which is featured in Fusion processors and AHCI 1.2 with SATA FIS-based switching support.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This is a chipset family supporting Phenom processors and Quad FX enthusiast platform (890FX), IGP (890GX).
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] With the advent of AMD's APUs in 2011, traditional northbridge features such as the connection to graphics and the PCI Express controller were incorporated into the APU die.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Accordingly, APUs were connected to a single chip chipset, renamed the Fusion Controller Hub (FCH), which primarily provided southbridge functionality.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD released new chipsets in 2017 to support the release of its new Ryzen products.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] As the Zen microarchitecture already includes much of the northbridge connectivity, the AM4-based chipsets primarily varied in the number of additional PCI Express lanes, USB connections, and SATA connections available.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] These AM4 chipsets were designed in conjunction with ASMedia.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In the early 1990s, AMD began marketing a series of embedded system-on-a-chips (SoCs) called AMD Élan, starting with the SC300 and SC310.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Both combines a 32-Bit, Am386SX, low-voltage 25 MHz or 33 MHz CPU with memory controller, PC/AT peripheral controllers, real-time clock, PLL clock generators and ISA bus interface.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The SC300 integrates in addition two PC card slots and a CGA-compatible LCD controller.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] They were followed in 1996 by the SC4xx types, now supporting VESA Local Bus and using the Am486 with up to 100 MHz clock speed.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] An SC450 at 33 MHz, for example, was used in the Nokia 9110 Communicator.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Using an Am586 with 100 MHz or 133 MHz and supporting SDRAM and PCI it was the latest member of the series.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In February 2002, AMD acquired Alchemy Semiconductor for its Alchemy line of MIPS processors for the hand-held and portable media player markets.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] On June 13, 2006, AMD officially announced that the line was to be transferred to Raza Microelectronics, Inc., a designer of MIPS processors for embedded applications.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In August 2003, AMD also purchased the Geode business which was originally the Cyrix MediaGX from National Semiconductor to augment its existing line of embedded x86 processor products.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] During the second quarter of 2004, it launched new low-power Geode NX processors based on the K7 Thoroughbred architecture with speeds of fanless processors 667 MHz and 1 GHz, and 1.4 GHz processor with fan, of TDP 25 W.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This technology is used in a variety of embedded systems (Casino slot machines and customer kiosks for instance), several UMPC designs in Asia markets, and the OLPC XO-1 computer, an inexpensive laptop computer intended to be distributed to children in developing countries around the world.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Geode LX processor was announced in 2005 and is said will continue to be available through 2015.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD has also introduced 64-bit processors into its embedded product line, starting with the AMD Opteron processor.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Leveraging the high throughput enabled through HyperTransport and the Direct Connect Architecture these server-class processors have been targeted at high-end telecom and storage applications.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2007, AMD added the AMD Athlon, AMD Turion, and Mobile AMD Sempron processors to its embedded product line.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Leveraging the same 64-bit instruction set and Direct Connect Architecture as the AMD Opteron but at lower power levels, these processors were well suited to a variety of traditional embedded applications.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The ATI acquisition in 2006 included the Imageon and Xilleon product lines.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In late 2008, the entire handheld division was sold off to Qualcomm, who have since produced the Adreno series.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Also in 2008, the Xilleon division was sold to Broadcom.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In April 2007, AMD announced the release of the M690T integrated graphics chipset for embedded designs.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This enabled AMD to offer complete processor and chipset solutions targeted at embedded applications requiring high-performance 3D and video such as emerging digital signage, kiosk, and Point of Sale applications.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The M690T was followed by the M690E specifically for embedded applications which removed the TV output, which required Macrovision licensing for OEMs, and enabled native support for dual TMDS outputs, enabling dual independent DVI interfaces.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In January 2011, AMD announced the AMD Embedded G-Series Accelerated Processing Unit.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This was the first APU for embedded applications.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] These were followed by updates in 2013 and 2016.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In May 2012, AMD announced the AMD Embedded R-Series Accelerated Processing Unit.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This family of products incorporates the Bulldozer CPU architecture, and Discrete-class Radeon HD 7000G Series graphics.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This was followed by a system-on-a-chip (SoC) version in 2015 which offered a faster CPU and faster graphics, with support for DDR4 SDRAM memory.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD builds graphic processors for use in embedded systems.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] They can be found in anything from casinos to healthcare, with a large portion of products being used in industrial machines.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] These products include a complete graphics processing device in a compact multi-chip module including RAM and the GPU.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] ATI began offering embedded GPUs with the E2400 in 2008.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Since then, AMD has released regular updates to its embedded GPU lineup in 2009, 2011, 2015, and 2016; reflecting improvements in its GPU technology.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In October 2020, AMD announced its acquisition of Xilinx, which was completed on February 14, 2022, through an all-stock transaction valued at approximately $60 billion.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Xilinx remained a wholly owned subsidiary of AMD until the brand was phased out in June 2023, with Xilinx's product lines now branded under AMD.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2011, AMD began selling Radeon branded DDR3 SDRAM to support the higher bandwidth needs of AMD's APUs.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] While the RAM is sold by AMD, it was manufactured by Patriot Memory and VisionTek.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This was later followed by higher speeds of gaming oriented DDR3 memory in 2013.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Radeon branded DDR4 SDRAM memory was released in 2015, despite no AMD CPUs or APUs supporting DDR4 at the time.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD noted in 2017 that these products are "mostly distributed in Eastern Europe" and that it continues to be active in the business.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD announced in 2014 that it would sell Radeon branded solid-state drives manufactured by OCZ with capacities up to 480 GB and using the SATA interface.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD has taken actions towards opening its software tools above the firmware level in the past decade.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Software not explicitly stated as being free can be assumed to be proprietary.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD Radeon Software is the default channel for official software distribution from AMD.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] It includes both free and proprietary software components, and supports both Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Most notable public AMD software is on the GPU side.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Previously, AMD produced its chips at company-owned semiconductor foundries.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD pursued a strategy of collaboration with other semiconductor manufacturers IBM and Motorola to co-develop production technologies.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD's founder Jerry Sanders termed this the "Virtual Gorilla" strategy to compete with Intel's significantly greater investments in fabrication.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Two former fabrication sites in Sunnyvale are listed as a Superfund site, added in 1986 and 1990 when volatile organic compounds were discovered in groundwater.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Acid neutralization system (ANS) tank vaults were discovered with holes when excavated with the contaminated soil.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2008, AMD spun off its chip foundries into an independent company named GlobalFoundries.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] This breakup of the company was attributed to the increasing costs of each process node.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] The Emirate of Abu Dhabi purchased the newly created company through its subsidiary Advanced Technology Investment Company (ATIC), purchasing the final stake from AMD in 2009.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] With the spin-off of its foundries, AMD became a fabless semiconductor manufacturer, designing products to be produced at for-hire foundries.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Part of the GlobalFoundries spin-off included an agreement with AMD to produce some number of products at GlobalFoundries.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] Both prior to the spin-off and after, AMD has pursued production with other foundries including TSMC and Samsung.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] It has been argued that this would reduce risk for AMD by decreasing dependence on any one foundry which has caused issues in the past.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] In 2018, AMD started shifting the production of its CPUs and GPUs to TSMC, following GlobalFoundries' announcement that it was halting development of its 7 nm process.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p02] AMD revised its wafer purchase requirement with GlobalFoundries in 2019, allowing AMD to freely choose foundries for 7 nm nodes and below, while maintaining purchase agreements for 12 nm and above through 2021.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] AMD has a long history of litigation with former (and current) partner and x86 creator Intel.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] AMD's sponsorship of Formula 1 racing began in 2002, and since 2020 has sponsored the Mercedes-AMG Petronas team.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] AMD was also a sponsor of the BMW Sauber and Scuderia Ferrari Formula 1 teams together with Intel, Vodafone, AT&T, Pernod Ricard and Diageo.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] On 18 April 2018, AMD began a multi-year sponsorship with Scuderia Ferrari.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] In February 2020, just prior to the start of the 2020 race season, the Mercedes Formula 1 team announced it was adding AMD to its sponsorship portfolio.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] AMD began a sponsorship deal with Victory Five (V5) for the League of Legends Pro League (LPL) in 2022.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] AMD was a sponsor of the Chinese Dota Pro Circuit together with Perfect World.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] In February 2024, AMD was a Diamond sponsor for the World Artificial Intelligence Cannes Festival (WAICF).
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] AMD was a Platinum sponsor for the HPE Discover 2024, an event hosted by Hewlett Packard Enterprise to showcase technology for government and business customers.
[src:desktop-computer/amd-p03] The event was held from 17 to 20 June 2024 in Las Vegas.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] A mathematical notation for manipulating arrays was developed by Kenneth E.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Iverson, starting in 1957 at Harvard University.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1960, he began work for IBM where he developed this notation with Adin Falkoff and published it in his book *A Programming Language* in 1962.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] This notation was used inside IBM for short research reports on computer systems, such as the Burroughs B5000 and its stack mechanism when stack machines versus register machines were being evaluated by IBM for upcoming computers.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Iverson also used his notation in a draft of the chapter *A Programming Language*, written for a book he was writing with Fred Brooks, *Automatic Data Processing*, which would be published in 1963.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1979, Iverson received the Turing Award for his work on APL.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] As early as 1962, the first attempt to use the notation to describe a complete computer system happened after Falkoff discussed with William C.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Carter his work to standardize the instruction set for the machines that later became the IBM System/360 family.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1963, Herbert Hellerman, working at the IBM Systems Research Institute, implemented a part of the notation on an IBM 1620 computer, and it was used by students in a special high school course on calculating transcendental functions by series summation.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Students tested their code in Hellerman's lab.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] This implementation of a part of the notation was called Personalized Array Translator (PAT).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1963, Falkoff, Iverson, and Edward H.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Sussenguth Jr., all working at IBM, used the notation for a formal description of the IBM System/360 series machine architecture and functionality, which resulted in a paper published in *IBM Systems Journal* in 1964.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] After this was published, the team turned their attention to an implementation of the notation on a computer system.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] One of the motivations for this focus of implementation was the interest of John L.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Lawrence who had new duties with Science Research Associates, an educational company bought by IBM in 1964.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Lawrence asked Iverson and his group to help use the language as a tool to develop and use computers in education.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Abrams of Stanford University joined the team at IBM Research, they continued their prior work on an implementation programmed in FORTRAN IV for a part of the notation which had been done for the IBM 7090 computer running on the IBSYS operating system.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] This work was finished in late 1965 and later named IVSYS (for Iverson system).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The basis of this implementation was described in detail by Abrams in a Stanford University Technical Report, "An Interpreter for Iverson Notation" in 1966.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The academic aspect of this was formally supervised by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Like Hellerman's PAT system earlier, this implementation omitted the APL character set, but used special English reserved words for functions and operators.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The system was later adapted for a time-sharing system and, by November 1966, it had been reprogrammed for the IBM System/360 Model 50 computer running in a time-sharing mode and was used internally at IBM.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] A key development in the ability to use APL effectively, before the wide use of cathode-ray tube (CRT) terminals, was the development of a special IBM Selectric typewriter interchangeable typing element with all the special APL characters on it.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] This was used on paper printing terminal workstations using the Selectric typewriter and typing element mechanism, such as the IBM 1050 and IBM 2741 terminal.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Keycaps could be placed over the normal keys to show which APL characters would be entered and typed when that key was struck.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] For the first time, a programmer could type in and see proper APL characters as used in Iverson's notation and not be forced to use awkward English keyword representations of them.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Falkoff and Iverson had the special APL Selectric typing elements, 987 and 988, designed in late 1964, although no APL computer system was available to use them.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Iverson cited Falkoff as the inspiration for the idea of using an IBM Selectric typing element for the APL character set.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Many APL symbols, even with the APL characters on the Selectric typing element, still had to be typed in by over-striking two extant element characters.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] An example is the *grade up* character, which had to be made from a *delta* (shift-H) and a *Sheffer stroke* (shift-M).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] This was necessary because the APL character set was much larger than the 88 characters allowed on the typing element, even when letters were restricted to upper-case (capitals).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The Tektronix 4013 Computer Display Terminal is a Tektronix 4010 with both the APL and ASCII character sets.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] There is a rocker switch above the keys to select the character set.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The first APL interactive login and creation of an APL workspace was in 1966 by Larry Breed using an IBM 1050 terminal at the IBM Mohansic Labs near Thomas J.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Watson Research Center, the home of APL, in Yorktown Heights, New York.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] IBM was chiefly responsible for introducing APL to the marketplace.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The first publicly available version of APL was released in 1968 for the IBM 1130.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] IBM provided *APL\1130* for free but without liability or support.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It would run in as little as 8k 16-bit words of memory, and used a dedicated 1 megabyte hard disk.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL gained its foothold on mainframe timesharing systems from the late 1960s through the early 1980s, in part because it would support multiple users on lower-specification systems that had no dynamic address translation hardware.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Additional improvements in performance for selected IBM System/370 mainframe systems included the *APL Assist Microcode* in which some support for APL execution was included in the processor's firmware, as distinct from being implemented entirely by higher-level software.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Somewhat later, as suitably performing hardware was finally growing available in the mid- to late-1980s, many users migrated their applications to the personal computer environment.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Early IBM APL interpreters for IBM 360 and IBM 370 hardware implemented their own multi-user management instead of relying on the host services, thus they were their own timesharing systems.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] First introduced for use at IBM in 1966, the *APL\360* system was a multi-user interpreter.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The ability to programmatically communicate with the operating system for information and setting interpreter system variables was done through special privileged "I-beam" functions, using both monadic and dyadic operations.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1973, IBM released *APL.SV*, which was a continuation of the same product, but which offered shared variables as a means to access facilities outside of the APL system, such as operating system files.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In the mid-1970s, the IBM mainframe interpreter was even adapted for use on the IBM 5100 desktop computer, which had a small CRT and an APL keyboard, when most other small computers of the time only offered BASIC.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In the 1980s, the *VSAPL* program product enjoyed wide use with Conversational Monitor System (CMS), Time Sharing Option (TSO), VSPC, MUSIC/SP, and CICS users.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Hagerty directed the implementation of the University of Maryland APL interpreter for the 1100 line of the Sperry UNIVAC 1100/2200 series mainframe computers.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1974, student Alan Stebbens was assigned the task of implementing an internal function.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Xerox APL was available from June 1975 for Xerox 560 and Sigma 6, 7, and 9 mainframes running CP-V and for Honeywell CP-6.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In the 1960s and 1970s, several timesharing firms arose that sold APL services using modified versions of the IBM APL\360 interpreter.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In North America, the better-known ones were IP Sharp Associates, Scientific Time Sharing Corporation (STSC), Time Sharing Resources (TSR), and The Computer Company (TCC).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] CompuServe also entered the market in 1978 with an APL Interpreter based on a modified version of Digital Equipment Corp and Carnegie Mellon's, which ran on DEC's KI and KL 36-bit machines.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] CompuServe's APL was available both to its commercial market and the consumer information service.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] With the advent first of less expensive mainframes such as the IBM 4300, and later the personal computer, by the mid-1980s, the timesharing industry was all but gone.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL interpreters were available from other mainframe and mini-computer manufacturers also, notably Burroughs, Control Data Corporation (CDC), Data General, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), Harris, Hewlett-Packard (HP), Siemens, Xerox and others.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Garth Foster of Syracuse University sponsored regular meetings of the APL implementers' community at Syracuse's Minnowbrook Conference Center in Blue Mountain Lake, New York.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In later years, Eugene McDonnell organized similar meetings at the Asilomar Conference Grounds near Monterey, California, and at Pajaro Dunes near Watsonville, California.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The SIGAPL special interest group of the Association for Computing Machinery continues to support the APL community.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] On microcomputers, which became available from the mid-1970s onwards, BASIC became the dominant programming language.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Nevertheless, some microcomputers provided APL instead – the first being the Intel 8008-based MCM/70 which was released in 1974 and which was primarily used in education.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Another machine of this time was the VideoBrain Family Computer, released in 1977, which was supplied with its dialect of APL called APL/S.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The Commodore SuperPET, introduced in 1981, included an APL interpreter developed by the University of Waterloo.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1976, Bill Gates claimed in his Open Letter to Hobbyists that Microsoft Corporation was implementing APL for the Intel 8080 and Motorola 6800 but had "very little incentive to make [it] available to hobbyists" because of software piracy.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Ken Iverson, no longer in control of the development of the APL language, left IBM and joined I.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Sharp Associates, where one of his major contributions was directing the evolution of Sharp APL to be more in accord with his vision.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL2 was first released for CMS and TSO in 1984.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The APL2 Workstation edition (Windows, OS/2, AIX, Linux, and Solaris) followed later.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] As other vendors were busy developing APL interpreters for new hardware, notably Unix-based microcomputers, APL2 was almost always the standard chosen for new APL interpreter developments.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Even today, most APL vendors or their users cite APL2 compatibility as a selling point for those products.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] IBM cites its use for problem solving, system design, prototyping, engineering and scientific computations, expert systems, for teaching mathematics and other subjects, visualization and database access.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Various implementations of APL by APLX, Dyalog, et al., include extensions for object-oriented programming, support for .NET, XML-array conversion primitives, graphing, operating system interfaces, and lambda calculus expressions.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Freeware versions include GNU APL for Linux and NARS2000 for Windows (which also runs on Linux under Wine).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Both of these are fairly complete versions of APL2 with various language extensions.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL has been criticized and praised for its choice of a unique character set.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In the 1960s and 1970s, few terminal devices or even displays could reproduce the APL character set.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The most popular ones employed the IBM Selectric print mechanism used with a special APL type element.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] One of the early APL line terminals (line-mode operation only, *not* full screen) was the Texas Instruments TI Model 745 (c.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] 1977) with the full APL character set which featured half and full duplex telecommunications modes, for interacting with an APL time-sharing service or remote mainframe to run a remote computer job, remote job entry (RJE).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Over time, with the universal use of high-quality graphic displays, printing devices and Unicode support, the APL character font problem has largely been eliminated.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] However, entering APL characters requires the use of input method editors, keyboard mappings, virtual/on-screen APL symbol sets, or easy-reference printed keyboard cards which can frustrate beginners accustomed to other programming languages.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] With beginners who have no prior experience with other programming languages, a study involving high school students found that typing and using APL characters did not hinder the students in any measurable way.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In defense of APL, it requires fewer characters to type, and keyboard mappings become memorized over time.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Special APL keyboards are also made and in use today, as are freely downloadable fonts for operating systems such as Microsoft Windows.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The reported productivity gains assume that one spends enough time working in the language to make it worthwhile to memorize the symbols, their semantics, keyboard mappings, and many idioms for common tasks.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Unlike traditionally structured programming languages, APL code is typically structured as chains of monadic or dyadic functions, and operators acting on arrays.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL has many nonstandard *primitives* (functions and operators) that are indicated by a single symbol or a combination of a few symbols.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] All primitives are defined to have the same precedence, and always associate to the right.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Thus, APL is *read* or best understood from right-to-left.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] 1970 or so) had no programming loop control flow structures, such as `do` or `while` loops, and `if-then-else` constructs.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Instead, they used array operations, and use of structured programming constructs was often unneeded, since an operation could be performed on a full array in one statement.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] For example, the `iota` function (`ι`) can replace for-loop iteration: ιN when applied to a scalar positive integer yields a one-dimensional array (vector), 1 2 3 ...
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Later APL implementations generally include comprehensive control structures, so that data structure and program control flow can be clearly and cleanly separated.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The APL environment is called a *workspace*.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In a workspace the user can define programs and data, i.e., the data values exist also outside the programs, and the user can also manipulate the data without having to define a program.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In the examples below, the APL interpreter first types six spaces before awaiting the user's input.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The user can save the workspace with all values, programs, and execution status.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL uses a set of non-ASCII symbols, which are an extension of traditional arithmetic and algebraic notation.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Having single character names for single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) vector functions is one way that APL enables compact formulation of algorithms for data transformation such as computing Conway's Game of Life in one line of code.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In nearly all versions of APL, it is theoretically possible to express any computable function in one expression, that is, in one line of code.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Due to the unusual character set, many programmers use special keyboards with APL keytops to write APL code.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Although there are various ways to write APL code using only ASCII characters, in practice it is almost never done.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] (This may be thought to support Iverson's thesis about notation as a tool of thought.) Most if not all modern implementations use standard keyboard layouts, with special mappings or input method editors to access non-ASCII characters.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Historically, the APL font has been distinctive, with uppercase italic alphabetic characters and upright numerals and symbols.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Most vendors continue to display the APL character set in a custom font.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Advocates of APL claim that the examples of so-called *write-only code* (badly written and almost incomprehensible code) are almost invariably examples of poor programming practice or novice mistakes, which can occur in any language.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Advocates also claim that they are far more productive with APL than with more conventional computer languages, and that working software can be implemented in far less time and with far fewer programmers than using other technology.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] They also may claim that because it is compact and terse, APL lends itself well to larger-scale software development and complexity, because the number of lines of code can be reduced greatly.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Many APL advocates and practitioners also view standard programming languages such as COBOL and Java as being comparatively tedious.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL is often found where time-to-market is important, such as with trading systems.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL makes a clear distinction between *functions* and *operators*.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Functions take arrays (variables or constants or expressions) as arguments, and return arrays as results.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Operators (similar to higher-order functions) take functions or arrays as arguments, and derive related functions.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] For example, the *sum* function is derived by applying the *reduction* operator to the *addition* function.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Applying the same reduction operator to the *maximum* function (which returns the larger of two numbers) derives a function which returns the largest of a group (vector) of numbers.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In the J language, Iverson substituted the terms *verb* for *function* and *adverb* or *conjunction* for *operator*.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL also identifies those features built into the language, and represented by a symbol, or a fixed combination of symbols, as *primitives*.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Most primitives are either functions or operators.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Coding APL is largely a process of writing non-primitive functions and (in some versions of APL) operators.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] However a few primitives are considered to be neither functions nor operators, most noticeably assignment.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Some words used in APL literature have meanings that differ from those in both mathematics and the generality of computer science.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL has explicit representations of functions, operators, and syntax, thus providing a basis for the clear and explicit statement of extended facilities in the language, and tools to experiment on them.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] A design theme in APL is to define default actions in some cases that would produce syntax errors in most other programming languages.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The 'Hello, world' string constant above displays, because display is the default action on any expression for which no action is specified explicitly (e.g. assignment, function parameter).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Another example of this theme is that exponentiation in APL is written as `2*3`, which indicates raising 2 to the power 3 (this would be written as `2^3` or `2**3` in some languages, or relegated to a function call such as `pow(2, 3);` in others).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Many languages use `*` to signify multiplication, as in `2*3`, but APL chooses to use `2×3`.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] However, if no base is specified (as with the statement `*3` in APL, or `^3` in other languages), most programming languages one would see this as a syntax error.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL, however, assumes the missing base to be the natural logarithm constant e, and interprets `*3` as `2.71828*3`.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Suppose that `X` is an array of numbers.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Reading *right-to-left*, `⍴X` gives the number of elements in X, and since `÷` is a dyadic operator, the term to its left is required as well.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It is surrounded by parentheses since otherwise X would be taken (so that the summation would be of `X÷⍴X`—each element of X divided by the number of elements in X), and `+/X` gives the sum of the elements of X.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Naturally, one would define this expression as a function for repeated use rather than rewriting it each time.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The above does a lot, concisely, although it may seem complex to a new APLer.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Since there is no function to the left of the left-most x to tell APL what to do with the result, it simply outputs it to the display (on a single line, separated by spaces) without needing any explicit instruction to do that.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] `?` also has a monadic equivalent called `roll`, which simply returns one random integer between 1 and its sole operand [to the right of it], inclusive.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Thus, a role-playing game program might use the expression `?20` to roll a twenty-sided die.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The following expression finds all prime numbers from 1 to R.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In both time and space, the calculation complexity is $O(R^{2})\,\!$ (in Big O notation).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] (This assumes the APL origin is 1, i.e., indices start with 1.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The following function "life", written in Dyalog APL, takes a Boolean matrix and calculates the new generation according to Conway's Game of Life.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It demonstrates the power of APL to implement a complex algorithm in very little code, but understanding it requires some advanced knowledge of APL (as the same program would in many languages).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL derives its name from the initials of Iverson's book *A Programming Language*, even though the book describes Iverson's mathematical notation, rather than the implemented programming language described in this article.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The name is used only for actual implementations, starting with APL\360.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] There has always been cooperation between APL vendors, and joint conferences were held on a regular basis from 1969 until 2010.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] At such conferences, APL merchandise was often handed out, featuring APL motifs or collection of vendor logos.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Common were apples (as a pun on the similarity in pronunciation of *apple* and *APL*) and the code snippet `⍺*⎕` which are the symbols produced by the classic APL keyboard layout when holding the APL modifier key and typing "APL".
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Despite all these community efforts, no universal vendor-agnostic logo for the programming language emerged.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL is used for many purposes including financial and insurance applications, artificial intelligence, neural networks and robotics.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It has been argued that APL is a calculation tool and not a programming language; its symbolic nature and array capabilities have made it popular with domain experts and data scientists who do not have or require the skills of a computer programmer.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL is well suited to image manipulation and computer animation, where graphic transformations can be encoded as matrix multiplications.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] One of the first commercial computer graphics houses, Digital Effects, produced an APL graphics product named *Visions*, which was used to create television commercials and animation for the 1982 film *Tron*.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Latterly, the Stormwind boating simulator uses APL to implement its core logic, its interfacing to the rendering pipeline middleware and a major part of its physics engine.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Today, APL remains in use in a wide range of commercial and scientific applications, asset management, health care, and DNA profiling.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The first implementation of APL using recognizable APL symbols was APL\360 which ran on the IBM System/360, and was completed in November 1966 though at that time remained in use only within IBM.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1973 its implementors, Larry Breed, Dick Lathwell and Roger Moore, were awarded the Grace Murray Hopper Award from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1975, the IBM 5100 microcomputer offered APL\360 as one of two built-in ROM-based interpreted languages for the computer, complete with a keyboard and display that supported all the special symbols used in the language.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Significant developments to APL\360 included CMS/APL, which made use of the virtual storage capabilities of CMS and APLSV, which introduced shared variables, system variables and system functions.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It was subsequently ported to the IBM System/370 and VSPC platforms until its final release in 1983, after which it was replaced by APL2.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1968, APL\1130 became the first publicly available APL system, created by IBM for the IBM 1130.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It became the most popular IBM Type-III Library software that IBM released.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL*Plus and Sharp APL are versions of APL\360 with added business-oriented extensions such as data formatting and facilities to store APL arrays in external files.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] They were jointly developed by two companies, employing various members of the original IBM APL\360 development team.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Sharp Associates (IPSA), an APL\360 services company formed in 1964 by Ian Sharp, Roger Moore and others, and STSC, a time-sharing and consulting service company formed in 1969 by Lawrence Breed and others.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Together the two developed APL*Plus and thereafter continued to work together but develop APL separately as APL*Plus and Sharp APL.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] STSC ported APL*Plus to many platforms with versions being made for the VAX 11, PC and UNIX, whereas IPSA took a different approach to the arrival of the personal computer and made Sharp APL available on this platform using additional PC-XT/360 hardware.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1993, Soliton Incorporated was formed to support Sharp APL and it developed Sharp APL into SAX (Sharp APL for Unix).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] As of 2018, APL*Plus continues as APL2000 APL+Win.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1985, Ian Sharp, and Dan Dyer of STSC, jointly received the Kenneth E.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Iverson Award for Outstanding Contribution to APL.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL2 was a significant re-implementation of APL by IBM which was developed from 1971 and first released in 1984.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It provides many additions to the language, of which the most notable is nested (non-rectangular) array support.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The entire APL2 Products and Services Team was awarded the Iverson Award in 2007.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 2021, IBM sold APL2 to Log-On Software, who develop and sell the product as *Log-On APL2*.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1972, APLGOL was released as an experimental version of APL that added structured programming language constructs to the language framework.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] New statements were added for interstatement control, conditional statement execution, and statement structuring, as well as statements to clarify the intent of the algorithm.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It was implemented for Hewlett-Packard in 1977.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Dyalog APL was first released by British company Dyalog Ltd. in 1983 and, as of 2018, is available for AIX, Linux (including on the Raspberry Pi), macOS and Microsoft Windows platforms.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It is based on APL2, with extensions to support object-oriented programming, functional programming, and tacit programming.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Licences are free for personal/non-commercial use.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In 1995, two of the development team – John Scholes and Peter Donnelly – were awarded the Iverson Award for their work on the interpreter.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Gitte Christensen and Morten Kromberg were joint recipients of the Iverson Award in 2016.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] NARS2000 is an open-source APL interpreter written by Bob Smith, a prominent APL developer and implementor from STSC in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] NARS2000 contains advanced features and new datatypes and runs natively on Microsoft Windows, and other platforms under Wine.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It is named after a development tool from the 1980s, NARS (Nested Arrays Research System).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APLX is a cross-platform dialect of APL, based on APL2 and with several extensions, which was first released by British company MicroAPL in 2002.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Although no longer in development or on commercial sale it is now available free of charge from Dyalog.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] York APL was developed at the York University, Ontario around 1968, running on IBM 360 mainframes.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] One notable difference between it and APL\360 was that it defined the "shape" (ρ) of a scalar as 1 whereas APL\360 defined it as the more mathematically correct 0 — this made it easier to write functions that acted the same with scalars and vectors.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] GNU APL is a free implementation of Extended APL as specified in ISO/IEC 13751:2001 and is thus an implementation of APL2.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] It runs on Linux, macOS, several BSD dialects, and on Windows (either using Cygwin for full support of all its system functions or as a native 64-bit Windows binary with some of its system functions missing).
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] GNU APL uses Unicode internally and can be scripted.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Richard Stallman, founder of the GNU Project, was an early adopter of APL, using it to write a text editor as a high school student in the summer of 1969.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL is traditionally an interpreted language, having language characteristics such as weak variable typing not well suited to compilation.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Most APL interpreters support idiom recognition and evaluate common idioms as single operations.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] For example, by evaluating the idiom `BV/⍳⍴A` as a single operation (where `BV` is a Boolean vector and `A` is an array), the creation of two intermediate arrays is avoided.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Weak typing in APL means that a name may reference an array (of any datatype), a function or an operator.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In general, the interpreter cannot know in advance which form it will be and must therefore perform analysis, syntax checking etc. at run-time.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] However, in certain circumstances, it is possible to deduce in advance what type a name is expected to reference and then generate bytecode which can be executed with reduced run-time overhead.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] This bytecode can also be optimised using compilation techniques such as constant folding or common subexpression elimination.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The interpreter will execute the bytecode when present and when any assumptions which have been made are met.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Dyalog APL includes support for optimised bytecode.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] Compilation of APL has been the subject of research and experiment since the language first became available; the first compiler is considered to be the Burroughs APL-700 which was released around 1971.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] In order to be able to compile APL, language limitations have to be imposed.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APEX is a research APL compiler which was written by Robert Bernecky and is available under the GNU General Public License.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] APL has been standardized by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) working group X3J10 and International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1 Subcommittee 22 Working Group 3.
[src:desktop-computer/apl-programming-language] The Core APL language is specified in ISO 8485:1989, and the Extended APL language is specified in ISO/IEC 13751:2001.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] Founded in 1985, the company listed publicly in 1993 and was acquired by AMD in 2006.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] As a major fabless semiconductor company, ATI conducted research and development in-house and outsourced the manufacturing and assembly of its products.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] With the decline and eventual bankruptcy of 3dfx in 2000, ATI and its chief rival Nvidia emerged as the two dominant players in the graphics processors industry, eventually forcing other manufacturers into niche roles.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] After acquiring ATI, AMD retained ATI Technologies as a subsidiary, but in 2010 AMD ceased using the ATI brand name, renaming its flagship Radeon graphics processor products with its branding instead.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] In addition to developing high-end GPUs (originally called a VPU by ATI) for PCs and Apple Macs, ATI also designed embedded versions for laptops (Mobility Radeon), PDAs and mobile phones (Imageon), integrated motherboards (Radeon IGP), and others.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] "Ruby", a fictional female character described as a "mercenary for hire", was created by ATI to promote some of its products.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] Computer-animated videos produced by RhinoFX about Ruby on a mission (being a sniper, saboteur, hacker and so on) appeared at large technology shows such as *CeBIT* and *CES*.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] However, high-end boards with IGP still used Intel GMA IGPs.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] The deal with Intel ended with the purchase of ATI by AMD in 2006, with Intel announcing SiS IGP chipset (D201GLY chipset, codenamed "*Little Valley*") for entry-level desktop platform, replacing the "*Grand County*" series chipsets.
[src:desktop-computer/ati-technologies] After the AMD acquisition, the Imageon and Xilleon were sold off to Qualcomm and Broadcom, respectively.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] A **desktop computer**, often abbreviated as **desktop**, is a personal computer designed for regular use at a stationary location on or near a desk (as opposed to a portable computer) due to its size and power requirements.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The case may be oriented horizontally or vertically and placed either underneath, beside, or on top of a desk.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Desktop computers with their cases oriented vertically are referred to as towers.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] As the majority of cases offered since the mid 1990s are in this form factor, the term *desktop* has been retronymically used to refer to modern cases offered in the traditional horizontal orientation.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Prior to the widespread use of microprocessors, a computer that could fit on a desk was considered remarkably small; the type of computers most commonly used were minicomputers, which, despite the name, were rather large and were "mini" only compared to the so-called "big iron".
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Early computers, and later the general purpose high throughput "mainframes", took up the space of a whole room.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Minicomputers, on the contrary, generally fit into one or a few refrigerator-sized racks, or, for the few smaller ones, *were built into* a fairly large desk, not put *on top* of it.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] It was not until the 1970s when fully programmable computers appeared that could fit entirely on top of a desk.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] 1970 saw the introduction of the Datapoint 2200, a "smart" computer terminal complete with keyboard and monitor, was designed to connect with a mainframe computer but that did not stop owners from using its built-in computational abilities as a stand-alone desktop computer.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The HP 9800 series, which started out as programmable calculators in 1971 but was programmable in BASIC by 1972, used a smaller version of a minicomputer design based on ROM memory and had small one-line LED alphanumeric displays and displayed graphics with a plotter.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The Wang 2200 of 1973 had a full-size cathode-ray tube (CRT) and cassette tape storage.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The IBM 5100 in 1975 had a small CRT display and could be programmed in BASIC and APL.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] These were generally expensive specialized computers sold for business or scientific uses.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Apple II, TRS-80 and Commodore PET were first-generation personal home computers launched in 1977, which were aimed at the consumer market – rather than businessmen or computer hobbyists.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] *Byte* magazine referred to these three as the "1977 Trinity" of personal computing.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, desktop computers became the predominant type, the most popular being the IBM PC and its clones, followed by the Apple Macintosh, with the third-placed Commodore Amiga having some success in the mid-1980s but declining by the early 1990s.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Over the course of the 1990s, desktop cases gradually became less common than the more-accessible tower cases that may be located on the floor under or beside a desk rather than on a desk.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Not only do these tower cases have more room for expansion, they have also freed up desk space for monitors which were becoming larger every year.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Desktop cases, particularly the compact form factors, remain popular for corporate computing environments and kiosks.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Some computer cases can be interchangeably positioned either horizontally (desktop) or upright (mini-tower).
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Creative Technology's Sound Blaster series were a *de facto* standard for sound cards in desktop PCs during the 1990s until the early 2000s, when they were reduced to a niche product, as OEM desktop PCs came with sound boards integrated directly onto the motherboard.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] While desktops have long been the most common configuration for PCs, by the mid-2000s the growth shifted from desktops to laptops.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Laptops had long been produced by contract manufacturers based in Asia, such as Foxconn, and this shift led to the closure of the many desktop assembly plants in the United States by 2010.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Another trend around this time was the increasing proportion of inexpensive base-configuration desktops being sold, hurting PC manufacturers such as Dell whose build-to-order customization of desktops relied on upselling added features to buyers.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Battery-powered portable computers had just a 2% worldwide market share in 1986.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] However, laptops have become increasingly popular, both for business and personal use.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Around 109 million notebook PCs shipped worldwide in 2007, a growth of 33% compared to 2006.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] In 2008, it was estimated that 145.9 million notebooks were sold and that the number would grow in 2009 to 177.7 million.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The third quarter of 2008 was the first time when worldwide notebook PC shipments exceeded desktops, with 38.6 million units versus 38.5 million units.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The sales breakdown of the Apple Macintosh has seen sales of desktop Macs staying mostly constant while being surpassed by that of Mac notebooks whose sales rate has grown considerably; seven out of ten Macs sold were laptops in 2009, a ratio projected to rise to three out of four by 2010.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The change in sales of form factors is due to the desktop iMac moving from affordable G3 to upscale G4 model and subsequent releases are considered premium all-in-ones.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The decades of development mean that most people already own desktop computers that meet their needs and have no need of buying a new one merely to keep pace with advancing technology.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Notably, the successive release of new versions of Windows (Windows 95, 98, XP, Vista, 7, 8, 10 and so on) had been drivers for the replacement of PCs in the 1990s, but this slowed in the 2000s.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] IDC analyst Jay Chou suggested that Windows 8 actually hurt sales of PCs in 2012, as businesses decided to stick with Windows 7 rather than upgrade.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Some suggested that Microsoft had acknowledged "implicitly ringing the desktop PC death knell" as Windows 8 offered little upgrade in desktop PC functionality over Windows 7; instead, Windows 8's innovations were mostly on the mobile side.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The post-PC trend saw a decline in the sales of desktop and laptop PCs.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The decline was attributed to increased power and applications of alternative computing devices, namely smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Among PC form factors, desktops remain a staple in the enterprise market but lost popularity among home buyers.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] In April 2017, StatCounter declared a "Milestone in technology history and end of an era" with the mobile Android operating system becoming more popular than Windows (the operating system that made desktops dominant over mainframe computers).
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Windows is still most popular on desktops (and laptops), while smartphones (and tablets) use Android or iOS.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Although for casual use traditional desktops and laptops have seen a decline in sales, in 2018, global PC sales experienced a resurgence, driven by the business market.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Desktops remain a solid fixture in the commercial and educational sectors.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] In 2019 the global PC market recorded its first full year of growth in eight years.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Inclusive of desktops, notebooks and workstations, 268.1 million units were shipped, up 2.7% on 2018.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] According to the International Data Corporation (IDC), PC sales shot up 14.8% between 2020 and 2021 and desktop market grew faster than the laptop market in the second quarter of 2021.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Total PC shipments during 2021 reached 348.8 million units, up 14.8% from 2020.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] This represents the highest level of shipments the PC market has seen since 2012.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] In addition, gaming desktops have seen a global revenue increase of 54% annually.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] For gaming the global market of gaming desktops, laptops, and monitors was expected to grow to 61.1 million shipments by the end of 2023, up from 42.1 million, with desktops growing from 15.1 million shipments to 19 million.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] PC gaming as a whole accounts for 28% of the total gaming market as of 2017.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] This is partially due to the increasing affordability of desktop PCs.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] In 2024 255.5 million PCs (including desktops and laptops) were shipped, up from 246 million in 2023 – a 3.8% year-over-year growth with Lenovo maintaining the largest market share.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] allow the workstation to be held sturdily upright in the tower configuration.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Full-sized desktops are characterized by separate display and processing components.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] These components are connected to each other by cables or wireless connections.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] These computers are easy to customize and upgrade per user requirements, e.g. by expansion card.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Early extended-size (significantly larger than mainstream ATX case) tower computers sometimes were labeled as "deskside computers", but currently this naming is quite rare.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Compact desktops are reduced in physical proportions compared to full-sized desktops.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] They are typically small-sized, inexpensive, low-power computers designed for basic tasks such as web browsing, accessing web-based applications, document processing, and audio/video playback.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Hardware specifications and processing power are usually reduced and hence make them less appropriate for running complex or resource-intensive applications.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] A nettop is a notable example of a compact desktop.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] A laptop without a screen can functionally be used as a compact desktop, sometimes called a "slabtop".
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] An *all-in-one* (AIO) desktop computer integrates the system's internal components into the same case as the display, thus occupying a smaller footprint (with fewer cables) than desktops that incorporate a tower.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The All-in-one systems are rarely labeled as desktop computers.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] In personal computing, a tower is a form factor of desktop computer case whose height is much greater than its width, thus having the appearance of an upstanding tower block.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] In computing, a pizza box enclosure is a design for desktop computers.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Pizza box cases tend to be wide and flat, resembling pizza delivery boxes, hence the name.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Cube Workstations have a cube case enclosure to house the motherboard, PCI-E expansion cards, GPU, CPU, DRAM DIMM slots, computer cooling equipment, chipsets, I/O ports, hard disk drives, and solid-state drives.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Open Frame cases have easy service access, and have no airflow problems, are great for building liquid-cooled systems and have an industrial design look, but will draw a lot of dust on components and needs cleaning them more often, yet the design allows blowing dust away with ease.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Gaming computers are desktop computers with high performance CPU, GPU, and RAM optimized for playing video games at high resolution and frame rates.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Gaming computer peripherals usually include mechanical keyboards for faster response time, and a gaming computer mouse which can track higher dots per inch movement.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] These desktops are connected to home entertainment systems and typically used for amusement purposes.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] They come with high definition display, video graphics, surround sound and TV tuner systems to complement typical PC features.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Over time some traditional desktop computers have been replaced with thin clients utilizing off-site computing solutions like the cloud.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] As more services and applications are served over the internet from off-site servers, local computing needs decrease, this drives desktop computers to be smaller, cheaper, and need less powerful hardware.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] More applications and in some cases entire virtual desktops are moved off-site and the desktop computer runs only an operating system or a shell application while the actual content is served from a server.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Thin client computers may do almost all of their computing on a virtual machine in another site.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Internal, hosted virtual desktops can offer users a completely consistent experience from anywhere.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Workstations are advanced class of personal computers designed for a user and more powerful than a regular PC but less powerful than a server in regular computing.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] They are capable of high-resolution and three-dimensional interfaces, and typically used to perform scientific and engineering work.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Like server computers, they are often connected with other workstations.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The main form-factor for this class is a Tower case, but most vendors produce compact or all-in-one low-end workstations.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Most tower workstations can be converted to a rack-mount version.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Oriented for small business class of servers; typically entry-level server machines, with similar to workstation/gaming PC computing powers and with some mainstream servers features, but with only basic graphic abilities; and some desktop servers can be converted to workstations.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Desktops have an advantage over laptops in that the spare parts and extensions tend to be standardized, resulting in lower prices and greater availability.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] For example, the size and mounting of the motherboard are standardized into ATX, microATX, BTX or other form factors.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Desktops have several standardized expansion slots, like conventional PCI or PCI Express, while laptops tend to have only one mini-PCI slot and one PC Card slot (or ExpressCard slot).
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Procedures for assembly and disassembly of desktops tend to be simple and standardized as well.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] This tends not to be the case for laptops, though adding or replacing some parts, like the optical drive, hard disk, or adding an extra memory module is often quite simple.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] This means that a desktop computer configuration, usually a tower case, can be customized and upgraded to a greater extent than laptops.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] This customization has kept tower cases popular among gamers and enthusiasts.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Another advantage of the desktop is that (apart from environmental concerns) power consumption is not as critical as in laptop computers because the desktop is exclusively powered from the wall socket.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Desktop computers also provide more space for cooling fans and vents to dissipate heat, allowing enthusiasts to overclock with less risk.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The two large microprocessor manufacturers, Intel and AMD, have developed special CPUs for mobile computers (e.g. laptops) that consume less power and lower heat, but with lower performance levels.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Laptop computers, conversely, offer portability that desktop systems (including small form factor and all-in-one desktops) cannot due to their compact size and clamshell design.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] The laptop's all-in-one design provides a built-in keyboard and a pointing device (such as a touchpad) for its user and can draw on power supplied by a rechargeable battery.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Laptops also commonly integrate wireless technologies like Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, and 3G, giving them a broader range of options for connecting to the internet, though this trend is changing as newer desktop computers come integrated with one or more of these technologies.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] A desktop computer needs a UPS to handle electrical disturbances like short interruptions, blackouts, and spikes; achieving an on-battery time of more than 20–30 minutes for a desktop PC requires a large and expensive UPS.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] A laptop with a sufficiently charged battery can continue to be used for hours in case of a power outage and is not affected by short power interruptions and blackouts.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] A desktop computer often has the advantage over a comparable laptop in computational capacity.
[src:desktop-computer/desktop-computer] Overclocking is often more feasible on a desktop than on a laptop; similarly, hardware add-ons such as discrete graphics co-processors may be possible to install only in a desktop.
